WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.200
[Amit Varma]: This episode of The Seen and The Unseen is brought to you by Intel.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:14.440
[Amit Varma]: What happened? In many ways, that's a more interesting question than what is.

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:18.720
[Amit Varma]: Yes, we want to know the state of the world, but we also want to know how we got here.

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:22.000
[Amit Varma]: We are wired to tell stories that explain the world to us.

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:27.760
[Amit Varma]: Because the world is complex, these explanations are always simplistic, but often useful.

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:33.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, to what extent does the usefulness of a narrative about the world depend on how true it is?

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:35.800
[Amit Varma]: Some narratives are false, but useful.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:37.480
[Amit Varma]: Religion is a perfect example.

00:00:37.640 --> 00:00:40.200
[Amit Varma]: How else could we deal with the thought of a mortality?

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:46.640
[Amit Varma]: Other narratives are false and they harm us by creating divisions in society and driving us apart.

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:52.960
[Amit Varma]: And hey, even true narratives can do this, which is why we should view history not as something we should take revenge for,

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:54.360
[Amit Varma]: but as a cautionary tale.

00:00:54.520 --> 00:00:56.880
[Amit Varma]: We should look back and learn what not to do.

00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes, be inspired by people who, in much worse circumstances than ours, have held firm and transcended their lives.

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:10.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, the thing with the stories that we tell about the world is that simple stories are often the most attractive and the least true.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:11.800
[Amit Varma]: Everything can be black and white.

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:13.680
[Amit Varma]: There are heroes, there are villains.

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:20.880
[Amit Varma]: The more of the truth that you capture, the more muddy things become, with shades of grey and moral ambiguities.

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:27.880
[Amit Varma]: That is why it is a big deal when someone who communicates good history, good in terms of getting as close to the truth as possible,

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:30.960
[Amit Varma]: is also a fine storyteller.

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:37.400
[Amit Varma]: History comes alive and can deepen our understanding of the world, when it is entertaining, not just enlightening.

00:01:37.560 --> 00:01:42.680
[Amit Varma]: In this world full of drama, we are all like jaded teenage Nirvana fans, screaming,

00:01:42.680 --> 00:02:00.920
[Unknown]: here we are now, entertain us.

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:02.320
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:10.000
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Amit Chandelier, a self-taught polymath who became a Twitter sensation a couple of years ago with his long threads on history.

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:11.920
[Amit Varma]: I'll link some of them from the show notes.

00:02:11.920 --> 00:02:15.400
[Amit Varma]: He has since gone on to write an ongoing show for storytell.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:21.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, I'm no slouch when it comes to reading history, but I've so often been surprised by some of Amit's threads,

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.200
[Amit Varma]: thinking to myself, wow, I didn't know that.

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:28.040
[Amit Varma]: He's given me more dots to join in my desire to paint an accurate picture of the world.

00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:30.920
[Amit Varma]: He's self-taught when it comes to both history and storytelling.

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And the phrase he uses to describe himself is history communicator.

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:38.600
[Amit Varma]: That's a damn good description and he's damn good at it.

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:42.720
[Amit Varma]: I think you'll agree after listening to this episode that not all Amits are evil.

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:48.400
[Amit Varma]: Akar Patel, please note, before we get to this conversation though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:50.880
[Amit Varma]: What is technology?

00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:52.080
[Amit Varma]: Let me put it like this.

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:54.920
[Amit Varma]: Back in the day, you had two big questions to answer.

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:56.320
[Amit Varma]: What do I want to do?

00:02:56.480 --> 00:02:57.480
[Amit Varma]: How do I do it?

00:02:57.640 --> 00:03:01.400
[Amit Varma]: The answer to that second question, how do I do this, is technology.

00:03:01.560 --> 00:03:07.480
[Amit Varma]: And the easier that how becomes, the more you can actually stretch yourself and get things done without friction.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:12.120
[Amit Varma]: The best technology, in fact, should be so invisible that you don't even notice it is there.

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:17.120
[Amit Varma]: An unseen force in making this happen is the sponsor of this episode, Intel.

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:22.400
[Amit Varma]: Now, everyone knows that Intel plays a key role in the architecture at the heart of the internet.

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:28.400
[Amit Varma]: But it also drives the technology at the edges, where users like you and me do what we do.

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:33.640
[Amit Varma]: Whether you're a radiologist or an engineer or a filmmaker or even a humble podcaster,

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:39.240
[Amit Varma]: chances are that whenever you do something wonderful, Intel is helping make it happen.

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.880
[Amit Varma]: Where there's an intelligent edge, there's Intel.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:45.600
[Amit Varma]: Amit, welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:46.480
[Amit Varma]: Thank you, Amit.

00:03:47.120 --> 00:03:53.400
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, this is, I think, the first time I've had another Amit on the show, though I have had Varma's in the past.

00:03:53.560 --> 00:04:00.200
[Amit Varma]: So, tell me something, I've been following you on Twitter, I've obviously loved your great history, threads and so on and so forth.

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:07.600
[Amit Varma]: But I don't know you otherwise. This is actually the first time we are meeting and I'm curious to know a little bit more about sort of your background.

00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:13.200
[Amit Varma]: How did you come to this? Were you always a lover of history? Were you always someone who read a lot of books?

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:18.600
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about the Amit Chandelier before you became Amit Chandelier, like before you became who you are, who were you?

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:23.360
[Guest]: Okay, I was just Amit Chandelier, nothing to do with history.

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:31.200
[Guest]: Nothing to do with history and my interest in history is not something new.

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:40.960
[Guest]: As a teenager, I remember when I was about 13 or 14, I read one book called Nina's Journey.

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:48.000
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a very, it's a ridiculously rare book and I had a copy at my place.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:54.560
[Guest]: And first of all, there was a book excerpt I had in one of the reader's digests that used to come out.

00:04:54.720 --> 00:05:01.240
[Guest]: It was monthly. And that excerpt triggered me into reading the full book.

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:08.440
[Guest]: And I come from a place where these things are not very easily accessible and from a time when these things were not very accessible.

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:19.960
[Guest]: But years later, I think, 3 or 4 years later, I was in Calcutta and I found a copy of the book at one of the used book sellers down the street.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:24.280
[Guest]: So, I read that book. I was about 14 at that time.

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:30.040
[Guest]: And that's an autobiography about a woman called Nina Markovna.

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:44.520
[Guest]: And she gave her story of how her dad, during Stalin's Russia, how her dad was killed and then how she managed to make her way to America, you know, and her adventures.

00:05:44.680 --> 00:05:52.760
[Guest]: She landed up in Germany and she initially thought that she was finally emancipated because she could have good food and good clothes.

00:05:52.760 --> 00:06:02.440
[Guest]: And then, very soon, she learned that Germany was not that safe space that she had thought of it as.

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:10.920
[Guest]: And then, she experienced both Stalin's Russia and Hitler's Germany towards the end of the World War.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:18.680
[Guest]: And that story stays with me till today. And like, I am in my 40s now and all these years.

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:25.480
[Guest]: And it changed something in me at that time because from school history, you just learn about good and evil.

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:33.800
[Guest]: Hitler bad, but the Allies good, you know, Mussolini bad, Bolsheviks good, Tsar's bad, you know, that kind of a history.

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:42.040
[Guest]: Then, this book gave me a new perspective that not just like even within evil, there are, you know, different kinds of evil.

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:47.160
[Guest]: They can be evil to each other and they still can come together to ruin the society at large.

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:58.040
[Guest]: So, I then started seeing nuance in history and then, you know, I came to Bombay later on and got busy with life and things just went on the back burner.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:02.120
[Guest]: I never thought of doing anything with it because here we are talking about early 2000s.

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:07.720
[Guest]: Couldn't do much. Like, you just learn and you feel that wow moment and move on with life.

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:21.000
[Guest]: And move on with life. Then, I have to really thank the right-wing surge since 2014 for a fresh interest in how things work on the history side.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:32.040
[Guest]: Now, what happened is, after 2014, we all must have noticed, there was a lot of surge in a very fresh, sometimes mischievous kind of interest in history.

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:40.520
[Guest]: And, you know, like either to rewrite history or to interpret it in the way that fits one narrative or the other.

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:52.600
[Guest]: There was a fresh interest and for better or for worse, it worked for me because it gave me an interest because a lot of new things started coming up which I had never known, never thought of.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:08:04.840
[Guest]: Things like, okay, yeah, there were some very cliched things like Taj Mahal used to be a Hindu temple. You know, those kind of things have been around since 2004-05 and we used to joke about them and never take them seriously.

00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:18.920
[Guest]: But from 2014 onwards, something very different happened. You know, a lot of things acquired a whole new nuance in a way that would seem believable to even the sanest amongst us.

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:24.680
[Guest]: You know, like things about Mahatma Gandhi, things about the Indian Independence Movement not giving due credit to Subhash Chandra Bose.

00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:33.400
[Guest]: Well, we grew up, you know, reading a lot about Subhash Chandra Bose. So, I made it a point that I would read first.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:42.760
[Guest]: So, I have been reading a lot of stories, not just Indian, but, you know, world history and short stories about the World Wars, things before the World War.

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:54.440
[Guest]: And, obviously, I absorbed a lot of new information. Then I came on Twitter. Twitter happened, I think, 2019, towards the end of 2019.

00:08:54.440 --> 00:09:09.640
[Guest]: And I did a short thread on Sadguru, Jaggi Vasudev. So, there was some crazy thing Jaggi Vasudev had put out where he said things like,

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:19.640
[Guest]: how shivling is, like pouring milk on shivling has a scientific, you know, rationale behind it and it absorbs radiation and all that nonsense.

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:29.720
[Guest]: So, I did a very short, seven tweets. That was the first thread of my Twitter life. So, I gave out a thread on how it's not scientific.

00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:37.400
[Guest]: Like a very neutral perspective, like nothing to do with, because I didn't know Sadguru before that. So, I said, this doesn't sound right.

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:49.400
[Guest]: You can't kill radiation with milk and there cannot be any special kind of radiation in a piece of rock or in a shivling, even if it's considered divine, because I consider it divine, the radiation doesn't.

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:56.920
[Guest]: So, those kind of things. I did one. Then a friend of mine told me that this thread has taken off. You should do something on the Indus Valley.

00:09:56.920 --> 00:10:10.920
[Guest]: You know, because there is a new narrative doing the rounds of WhatsApp groups that the Aryans emerged like 10, 12, 20,000 years ago in India and then they spread all over the world and the whole world is Aryan.

00:10:10.920 --> 00:10:22.920
[Guest]: I was like, that's rubbish. No sane person would take that seriously. She's like, no, you're wrong. It's becoming the mainstream dominant piece of history on at least social media.

00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:33.920
[Guest]: I'm like, okay, fine. Let me do something. So, I just gathered bits and pieces of whatever I could find on Indus Valley, the latest research. I wanted to be as objective as possible.

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:48.920
[Guest]: And I did a thread. That thread took off and then I realized, I mean, I got a lot of, you know, a lot of abusive responses to that. I got threats because, you know, of course.

00:10:48.920 --> 00:11:08.920
[Guest]: So, that was my first interface with the cancel culture. And then it gave me a germ that history has to be communicated. There is something terribly wrong with history, the way history is being taught and it has to be communicated.

00:11:08.920 --> 00:11:22.920
[Guest]: And then I assumed the position of a communicator and I started doing threads on a more regular basis, like at least once every week or once, you know, once every two weeks, I started doing threads.

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:34.920
[Guest]: Initially, I would just put out the story and then I realized, okay, no, people, there are controversial things. I need to put out some kind of an evidence or some reference for whatever I'm speaking about.

00:11:34.920 --> 00:11:47.920
[Guest]: So, then, you know, the research grew over time. A lot of nuances. I mean, there are threads from 2019, I might not enjoy reading myself today. So, it's grown over time.

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:58.920
[Guest]: Then, at some point in time, last year, 2020, I got a text from Storytel saying, would you be interested in doing a series for us?

00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:07.920
[Guest]: And I agreed. First of all, I was like flabbergasted. That was the first time somebody asked me to do something professional. Seriously, do these things happen?

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:15.920
[Guest]: You just do Twitter threads and people take you that seriously that they ask you to do professional work? I was like, yeah, fine, why not?

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:27.920
[Guest]: So, that was my first break into doing something to do with history on a professional level. I did that and that's a running gig. I continue doing it today.

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:40.920
[Guest]: And then there was a tweet series I did on the locust plague, if you remember, that happened last year. I got a call from Times of India, Mumbai Mirror.

00:12:40.920 --> 00:12:49.920
[Guest]: They asked me to do an article for their paper and I did that. So, yeah, the more opportunities I got, the more it became a serious part of my day to day life.

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:57.920
[Amit Varma]: I feel firstly, you're being too harsh on yourself when you say that you might not like some of your older threads from 2019.

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:02.920
[Amit Varma]: From whenever I've been reading you, I've absolutely loved your threads and they're very different from other history threads.

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:13.920
[Amit Varma]: In A, the amount of detail that is there and B, most startlingly, the storytelling. Like you really know how to kind of build a story up and take it to a particular place and make it work.

00:13:13.920 --> 00:13:21.920
[Amit Varma]: Most spectacularly, the one that I remembered as memorable for me is the one on Martin Luther King, where you have this massive kind of narrative happening.

00:13:21.920 --> 00:13:26.920
[Amit Varma]: And then that beautiful way in which it ends, which I won't give a spoiler, I'll just link it from the show notes.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:35.920
[Amit Varma]: But it's almost like you couldn't help but be moved and affected and just blown away at the end of it, just in the way that you told the story.

00:13:35.920 --> 00:13:41.920
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, all the facts of the story matter, the facts of history matter, but the storytelling makes it stand out.

00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, couple of questions here, like how much conscious effort has there been on your part to work on the craft of storytelling?

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:55.920
[Amit Varma]: Because the craft is outstanding. It's obviously something that, you know, thought about and worked at over a period of time.

00:13:55.920 --> 00:14:06.920
[Amit Varma]: So, what is the kind of effort that you put into it? And also, who are the kind of storytellers then, in a historical or even an out of history context, who impressed you?

00:14:06.920 --> 00:14:09.920
[Amit Varma]: Who, you know, made you think that, yeah, that's the way to do it?

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:19.920
[Guest]: To answer your first question, yes, storytelling as a craft, like, yes, there is a certain structure, which you have noticed, a lot of other people have noticed,

00:14:19.920 --> 00:14:27.920
[Guest]: that it's a three part thing, if you will, where there's a build up and then there is a climax and then there is a cliffhanger kind of thing.

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:38.920
[Guest]: So, no, I wouldn't say it's a very natural thing, it just happened. No, there is a very deliberate effort involved there. It doesn't happen.

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:48.920
[Guest]: Now, why I did that, there's a reason for that. Because it's not that there is any shortage of historical accounts all around us, with or without me.

00:14:48.920 --> 00:15:01.920
[Guest]: The stories are all around us. But still, why history has, over the years, over the past few decades, history has taken, assumed, for the lack of a better word,

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:09.920
[Guest]: a status of something very boring and mundane and not you want to proudly tell anyone about being into.

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:17.920
[Guest]: You know, you say you're into science, you're into quantum physics, you're into medicine, engineering, but nobody says I want to do a major in history.

00:15:17.920 --> 00:15:23.920
[Guest]: And at least in India. So, why history became, it's become a running trope, right?

00:15:23.920 --> 00:15:28.920
[Guest]: You know, history is such a boring subject at schools. You have to memorize so many dates, so many names.

00:15:28.920 --> 00:15:42.920
[Guest]: So, yes, it is boring. And then I realized that part of the reason, a big part of the reason is that the way history has been taught to us and recounted in historical accounts, in history books, is very linear.

00:15:42.920 --> 00:15:50.920
[Guest]: You know, when Babur came in and he ruled for so many years, then Humayun took over. Humayun was beaten. He went to Afghanistan in exile and then came back.

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:57.920
[Guest]: Not Afghanistan, sorry, Persia. And then he came back and then he ruled for a certain number of years, Akbar and Aurangzeb and so on and so forth.

00:15:57.920 --> 00:16:04.920
[Guest]: It doesn't trigger any interest. It doesn't trigger any sense of awe that, wow, I didn't know this, you know.

00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:16.920
[Guest]: So, my idea was to, okay, I'm not creating any new story. I'm just, you know, repackaging the same story, but I have to do it differently just to create that interest.

00:16:16.920 --> 00:16:26.920
[Guest]: And you cannot create interest without making people go, wow, I didn't know that. That has to be the dominant emotion when they're reading your story.

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:33.920
[Guest]: Of course, research is involved. A lot of research is involved, but my primary focus was on communication.

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:39.920
[Guest]: I have to be, I'm not a historian, right? I prefer to say I'm a history communicator.

00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:47.920
[Guest]: My job is to communicate. So, I have two approaches to whatever I write, be it my threads or with story tell, anywhere.

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:58.920
[Guest]: Either the story has to have at least something that you didn't have earlier. Before the story, you didn't know something, right?

00:16:58.920 --> 00:17:09.920
[Guest]: So, that has to be one criteria. Another criteria is, it's the same story, but there is yet another story that seems very unrelated, you know.

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:18.920
[Guest]: And somehow, I want to show that story A, which seems very unrelated to story B, had an impact on story B.

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:28.920
[Guest]: You know, B wouldn't have happened if A didn't. And then you realize, wow, really, these two are like, these two happened such different times and spaces

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:36.920
[Guest]: that it was impossible that anyone would have imagined. The popular term for this is butterfly effect.

00:17:36.920 --> 00:17:42.920
[Guest]: So, butterfly effect is a very big part of my conscious effort of telling a story.

00:17:42.920 --> 00:17:50.920
[Guest]: For example, this thread I did on Aksai Chen. Yeah, fine, there is a dispute between India and China and Aksai Chen has been going on for the past.

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:57.920
[Guest]: Now, everyone knows what the dispute is all about and why. And yes, the Indochina war and everything.

00:17:57.920 --> 00:18:09.920
[Guest]: But then I wanted to show people that this dispute was, you know, seeded long before there was a China as we know it today or an India as we know it today.

00:18:09.920 --> 00:18:16.920
[Guest]: And the original actors in the game were not even India and China. They were France and Russia.

00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:23.920
[Guest]: These are Alexander I, Nicholas's great-grandfather and Napoleon Bonaparte. That's a more famous name. Everyone knows.

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:30.920
[Guest]: So, these two struck a deal somewhere in today's Poland and they decided to help each other.

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:37.920
[Guest]: Like France would help Russia against the Ottomans and Russia would help France against the British.

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:42.920
[Guest]: Because France and Britain, they have a very long story going back thousands of years.

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:48.920
[Guest]: So, that was the treaty sometime in the early 19th century, 1807 if I'm not wrong.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:55.920
[Guest]: And then that treaty triggered Russian interest in the Afghanistan region, Afghanistan-Kashmir region.

00:18:55.920 --> 00:19:03.920
[Guest]: That if they had Kashmir or Afghanistan, they could build a good buffer against the British because India was British, right?

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:14.920
[Guest]: So, that's when the great game began and that's how Afghanistan ended up being, you know, the epicenter of all kinds of political nonsense that we see till date.

00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:20.920
[Guest]: So, nobody would have connected Napoleon Bonaparte with the Aksai Chin issue.

00:19:20.920 --> 00:19:23.920
[Guest]: But that was the whole approach I took.

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:33.920
[Guest]: Because at the end of the story, people have to appreciate that things that might seem very unrelated, both geographically and temporarily, can be related.

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:40.920
[Guest]: One thing can lead to, you know, it's a rabbit hole. History is just a network of rabbit holes, if you read.

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:43.920
[Guest]: So, that is a very conscious effort.

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And I feel that there is a lesson in this kind of approach to history.

00:19:49.920 --> 00:19:54.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, I have the same approach, but I haven't done the kind of work you have with that kind of rigor.

00:19:54.920 --> 00:19:59.920
[Amit Varma]: But an approach in the sense that I'm always entering into rabbit holes and going off in all kinds of directions.

00:19:59.920 --> 00:20:06.920
[Amit Varma]: But the lesson here is this, and the lesson is that the world is complex and we have to accept it in all its complexity.

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:15.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, I think there is one danger when a natural tendency we have, and we hardwire to do this, that we build simple narratives to explain the world.

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And also, everything that has already happened, it seems inevitable.

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:21.920
[Amit Varma]: Because it has already happened. It's a hindsight bias.

00:20:21.920 --> 00:20:25.920
[Amit Varma]: Though at a particular point in time, a million things can happen and then one thing does.

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:29.920
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of it is luck and chance and accident. But, you know, it is what it is.

00:20:29.920 --> 00:20:34.920
[Amit Varma]: We don't think in probabilistic ways. So, we assume that whatever happened was inevitable.

00:20:34.920 --> 00:20:38.920
[Amit Varma]: And then equally, we assume a directionality to it, a teleological thing.

00:20:38.920 --> 00:20:43.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, there is this thing that, you know, even within our culture, we will say everything happens for a reason.

00:20:43.920 --> 00:20:48.920
[Amit Varma]: Though typically we say this to someone when something bad has happened to them, but everything happens for a reason.

00:20:48.920 --> 00:20:52.920
[Amit Varma]: And we almost have this sense about history that everything is linear.

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:58.920
[Amit Varma]: Everything is leading on to what it appears to lead on to and so on and so forth.

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:02.920
[Amit Varma]: And we look at certain characters in, you know, in black and white rather than shades of grey.

00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:06.920
[Amit Varma]: And of course, as has become a cliche on my show to say everybody contains multitudes,

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:13.920
[Amit Varma]: especially our great figures like Gandhi onwards. They are deeply complex people with many kind of shades to them.

00:21:13.920 --> 00:21:20.920
[Amit Varma]: And I guess what your work shows or what any historian who is embracing this complexity,

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:25.920
[Amit Varma]: what they realize and what they bring out for the readers is that no, shit is not simple.

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:30.920
[Amit Varma]: That, you know, everything is deeply complex. We are shaped by history, of course,

00:21:30.920 --> 00:21:33.920
[Amit Varma]: in ways that we possibly cannot even fully understand.

00:21:33.920 --> 00:21:37.920
[Amit Varma]: And we have to transcend it and all of those things.

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:44.920
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel that, A, while going deep into these rabbit holes, while following these butterfly effects yourself,

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:49.920
[Amit Varma]: do you feel that you also changed as a person in the way that you kind of view nuance

00:21:49.920 --> 00:21:52.920
[Amit Varma]: or the way that you sort of view the world?

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:58.920
[Amit Varma]: And do you feel that the study of history in this way is therefore important for that reason?

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:02.920
[Guest]: Of course, every story I do, every thread I have finished has...

00:22:02.920 --> 00:22:08.920
[Guest]: Okay, fine. It has taught me something new about certain part of history I hadn't touched before that.

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:13.920
[Guest]: It's as much a learning experience for me as it is for anyone reading the thread.

00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:19.920
[Guest]: But yes, it does. It does create a lot of change in myself because

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:30.920
[Guest]: you discover things about a person on whom, you know, a historical character or an entity or a group of people.

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:37.920
[Guest]: You learn something about that entity that changes how you viewed them so far.

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:43.920
[Guest]: And we all start reading history with some or the other prejudice, let's face it.

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:47.920
[Guest]: It's not just a right-wing, left-wing thing. We all have our prejudices.

00:22:47.920 --> 00:22:51.920
[Guest]: Like when you talk about Indian independence movement, you know, British Raj and we all...

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:58.920
[Guest]: It's a very established prejudice, British evil, Indian, you know, Indian victims.

00:22:58.920 --> 00:23:03.920
[Guest]: And it goes on in every sphere of history, like, you know, with the Mughals also.

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:14.920
[Guest]: But then my view is every time I do a thread, I learn that yes, there are evil people, there are victims, there are perpetrators.

00:23:14.920 --> 00:23:20.920
[Guest]: But there's a whole lot more of grey than, you know, good or bad.

00:23:20.920 --> 00:23:23.920
[Guest]: History cannot be monochromatic. History cannot be...

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:28.920
[Guest]: And history is far more interesting than, you know, the good prevailing over the bad.

00:23:28.920 --> 00:23:37.920
[Guest]: Now, that is one thing. Another thing is, I don't even know how you can change the curriculum to involve so much of nuance.

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:47.920
[Guest]: When you're talking about history as an academic rigor, when you're talking about history at the school level, I don't think you can teach this.

00:23:47.920 --> 00:23:55.920
[Guest]: It has to be, I mean, from just my perspective as it stands today, I don't see a solution to that.

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:59.920
[Guest]: You have to teach them history the way the textbooks are written.

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:06.920
[Guest]: But then eventually, if you have some kind of an interest, because in India, first of all, there is no interest in history.

00:24:06.920 --> 00:24:11.920
[Guest]: And there is no interest in history because there is no prospects.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:19.920
[Guest]: There is no future. Like if you, say, do a major in history, what are your options in terms of livelihood?

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:23.920
[Guest]: Until those things are fixed, people are not going to have any interest.

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:27.920
[Guest]: I came out of the same schooling system and I developed an interest.

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:31.920
[Guest]: So, interest is a very personal thing you can develop.

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:38.920
[Guest]: What people like me can do is, the role I am playing is a very casual approach to, you know,

00:24:38.920 --> 00:24:43.920
[Guest]: acquainting you with the parts that are missing in whatever you read so far.

00:24:43.920 --> 00:24:49.920
[Guest]: The nuances of maybe you know the story, but you didn't know it could be seen in this light.

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:58.920
[Guest]: So, for example, like I did a video with Storytel and I was very controversial about the Jallianwala Bagh thing, about Dyer.

00:24:58.920 --> 00:25:03.920
[Guest]: Now, we know Dyer came, he shot, he opened fire and a lot of people died.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:07.920
[Guest]: I think there were some accounts, say, up to 10,000 people.

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:12.920
[Guest]: I don't know what exactly the true number was, would have been.

00:25:12.920 --> 00:25:17.920
[Guest]: But hardly anyone knows Dyer's story.

00:25:17.920 --> 00:25:27.920
[Guest]: Now, the moment you utter the phrase, Dyer's story, I am not saying Dyer's side of the story, I am saying Dyer's story,

00:25:27.920 --> 00:25:31.920
[Guest]: it triggers, it, you know, it brings back memory, like historical memory.

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:34.920
[Guest]: Okay, he was a villain. How can we talk about his story?

00:25:34.920 --> 00:25:37.920
[Guest]: We don't need to know who he was.

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:42.920
[Guest]: Now, the fact is when Dyer came, showed up on the scene, you have to understand that

00:25:42.920 --> 00:25:50.920
[Guest]: India was a British colony for almost a century and a half, right?

00:25:50.920 --> 00:26:00.920
[Guest]: So, Dyer was born in India. His parents had been living in India for, I think, 10, 20, 30 years.

00:26:00.920 --> 00:26:06.920
[Guest]: So, he was, at least to himself, he was as much an Indian as anyone else.

00:26:06.920 --> 00:26:12.920
[Guest]: Like, as an American, who would have been involved with the American War of Independence, George Washington,

00:26:12.920 --> 00:26:17.920
[Guest]: he considered himself American, but those people were not technically American, right?

00:26:17.920 --> 00:26:24.920
[Guest]: They were all migrants from UK, but they became patriotic about America and they fought the War of Independence.

00:26:24.920 --> 00:26:31.920
[Guest]: But at the same time, it's very common knowledge what people like Thomas Jefferson did to the natives in America, right?

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:36.920
[Guest]: So, but we don't question their patriotism because they felt they were patriots and that's a dominant theme there.

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:45.920
[Guest]: Now, in India, it was the same emotion Dyer came with, that he considered himself Indian and the natives,

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:49.920
[Guest]: let's say, sub-Indian, if not non-Indian or non-entities.

00:26:49.920 --> 00:26:56.920
[Guest]: But to him, he was serving India by, you know, wiping out the natives and, you know, clearing the space.

00:26:56.920 --> 00:27:03.920
[Guest]: And so much so, that when he went to Ireland for his higher studies, he spoke fluent Hindi.

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:09.920
[Guest]: He carried his Hindi books to ensure that he keeps practicing Hindi, not to forget the language.

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:12.920
[Guest]: It was his mother tongue. That's the language he spoke in his household.

00:27:12.920 --> 00:27:17.920
[Guest]: And he was bullied in Ireland. You know the relation between, you know, England and Ireland.

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:21.920
[Guest]: And those times, it was at the like the lowest point.

00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:27.920
[Guest]: And the Irish kids would bully him saying, you're not even white, you're Indian.

00:27:27.920 --> 00:27:34.920
[Guest]: He was white, but he was seen more as Indian amongst his peers than British.

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:38.920
[Guest]: So, these are nuances. What to do with that nuance? I don't know.

00:27:38.920 --> 00:27:46.920
[Guest]: Is it meant to justify what he did? No. But it happened and this is a piece of history you just can't wish away.

00:27:46.920 --> 00:27:51.920
[Guest]: So, it might be uncomfortable, but it's there.

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:57.920
[Guest]: When you study history, you have to be passionate about the story and not the characters.

00:27:57.920 --> 00:28:04.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. You know, you said earlier that Indians haven't had an interest in history and that, of course, is true.

00:28:04.920 --> 00:28:09.920
[Amit Varma]: That's partly down to, as you mentioned, the way that it's taught. It's all rote learning, your mugging updates and all of that.

00:28:09.920 --> 00:28:12.920
[Amit Varma]: And also, you mentioned that there are no career prospects.

00:28:12.920 --> 00:28:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And from that point of view, yeah, there won't be many Indians who are interested in taking it up in a professional way

00:28:18.920 --> 00:28:21.920
[Amit Varma]: unless they're kind of going to a foreign university and they can make a career there.

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:25.920
[Amit Varma]: But in a different context, I would say that there's enormous interest in history.

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:31.920
[Amit Varma]: Like we were mentioning before this while having lunch that of all my episodes, the history episodes do really well.

00:28:31.920 --> 00:28:36.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, some of my most popular episodes are with people like Manu Pillay and Srinath Raghavan, for example,

00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:43.920
[Amit Varma]: which are episodes that I myself learnt a lot from and which sent me down various kind of rabbit holes.

00:28:43.920 --> 00:28:47.920
[Amit Varma]: And I think here's the thing that history as a calling and a vocation is one thing.

00:28:47.920 --> 00:28:52.920
[Amit Varma]: That might depend on things like the incentives around you and the career prospects and all of that.

00:28:52.920 --> 00:28:57.920
[Amit Varma]: But history is a hobby. History is something everyone wants to delve into. It's an entirely different matter.

00:28:57.920 --> 00:29:02.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, as humans, we are always in search of drama. That's why we watch sport.

00:29:02.920 --> 00:29:05.920
[Amit Varma]: We watch sport for the individual drama, right?

00:29:05.920 --> 00:29:10.920
[Amit Varma]: We would not watch, say, like a chess game between two AI bots would be really boring to us.

00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:14.920
[Amit Varma]: But when it's people and we know their stories and their stories brings it alive.

00:29:14.920 --> 00:29:21.920
[Amit Varma]: And for exactly that reason, I feel that there is a huge hunger there for history because history has drama.

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:22.920
[Amit Varma]: History has stories.

00:29:22.920 --> 00:29:30.920
[Amit Varma]: When I did my first episode with Manu on his book on the Deccan and I happened to remark that there was more violence in that book

00:29:30.920 --> 00:29:33.920
[Amit Varma]: and more crazy characters and more action and drama than in Game of Thrones.

00:29:33.920 --> 00:29:38.920
[Amit Varma]: And it's true. And there is because there's kind of so much happening there.

00:29:38.920 --> 00:29:44.920
[Amit Varma]: And this whole thing about humanizing these people is also really interesting to me.

00:29:44.920 --> 00:29:46.920
[Amit Varma]: Like even in the case of Daya, see, that's the point.

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:52.920
[Amit Varma]: Unfortunately, in the times that we live in, even with what you said just now, those type of people, the vocal minorities,

00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:56.920
[Amit Varma]: I don't think have the intellectual capacity to listen to podcasts for too long.

00:29:56.920 --> 00:29:58.920
[Amit Varma]: So they probably haven't gotten here.

00:29:58.920 --> 00:30:04.920
[Amit Varma]: But there are people, if you said that on Twitter, who would obviously misinterpret that as a defense of General Daya.

00:30:04.920 --> 00:30:05.920
[Amit Varma]: They did.

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:06.920
[Amit Varma]: They did. Oh, this happened.

00:30:06.920 --> 00:30:12.920
[Guest]: I was heavily trolled for that. But you can troll me. You can't troll history. That's the thing.

00:30:12.920 --> 00:30:19.920
[Amit Varma]: But does history matter? I mean, in the sense that where we live today is in a world full of competing narratives, right?

00:30:19.920 --> 00:30:21.920
[Amit Varma]: History has already happened and in that sense is gone.

00:30:21.920 --> 00:30:26.920
[Amit Varma]: And you can say that history lives on in terms of its consequences and what it has shaped.

00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:33.920
[Amit Varma]: But equally, there is a lot that, you know, there are false narratives that have consequences and that shape people around us.

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:35.920
[Amit Varma]: Which is the other thing that I worry about.

00:30:35.920 --> 00:30:44.920
[Amit Varma]: That on the one hand, I'm really happy that there are popular historians like Manu and Srinath and, you know, hopefully you as we go along,

00:30:44.920 --> 00:30:51.920
[Amit Varma]: who at least play a part in popularizing stories of history and making people become more open to it.

00:30:51.920 --> 00:30:54.920
[Amit Varma]: But then the point is, do the facts matter? We are all following narratives.

00:30:54.920 --> 00:31:01.920
[Amit Varma]: Like I was watching this video, one of you, I think your only video on YouTube, which you did for Storytel at their launch.

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:05.920
[Amit Varma]: And at some point you mentioned the phrase when the Aryans came to India.

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:10.920
[Amit Varma]: And on the comments, people jumped on you because they're saying the invasion theory is bunkum.

00:31:10.920 --> 00:31:14.920
[Amit Varma]: And the fact is, we know it's not bunkum. You know, you've referred to a book by David Reich.

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:18.920
[Amit Varma]: I've had Tony Joseph on my podcast. He's got a great book, Early Indians, about it.

00:31:18.920 --> 00:31:26.920
[Amit Varma]: There's enough evidence by now from different fields, including genetics, that tells us that, you know, there was an Aryan migration.

00:31:26.920 --> 00:31:32.920
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, even language. I had an episode with Peggy Mohan where she traces the sort of...

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and a lovely, lovely book, Wanderer's King's Merchants, where she traces...

00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:42.920
[Amit Varma]: She does a forensic study of how our languages have evolved and you can make out so much of history from that.

00:31:42.920 --> 00:31:47.920
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is that the evidence doesn't matter. This is never going to be settled.

00:31:47.920 --> 00:31:53.920
[Amit Varma]: It's never going to be settled because one set of people want to believe something and another set of people want to believe something else.

00:31:53.920 --> 00:32:04.920
[Guest]: Yeah, the problem, I mean, either say it's a good thing about history or a problem, but you can prove whatever you want.

00:32:04.920 --> 00:32:12.920
[Guest]: That's the thing with the amount of resources we have all around us and the amount of, you know, you have all kinds of resources, right?

00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:21.920
[Guest]: Now, today, I write a book with a certain agenda and that book gets a decent publisher.

00:32:21.920 --> 00:32:26.920
[Guest]: Four years down the line, that book becomes a resource for someone to refer to, right?

00:32:26.920 --> 00:32:32.920
[Guest]: And then you can carry on with the same agenda and you can quote me and you have a credible source.

00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:38.920
[Guest]: Now, but was I credible in the first place or did I come from a place of, you know, colored agenda?

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:45.920
[Guest]: So today, it's the same thing happening with history that you want to prove Aryans came into India.

00:32:45.920 --> 00:32:53.920
[Guest]: You have resources, you can quote. You want to prove Aryans originated in India 20,000 years ago and they spread to America.

00:32:53.920 --> 00:32:58.920
[Guest]: You have resources to prove that also. I mean, as far as just textual resources go.

00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:00.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, they might be bunkum at the heart of it.

00:33:00.920 --> 00:33:12.920
[Guest]: Exactly, but who cares? Like end of the day, if you have a long bibliography or if you have screenshots of, you know, yellowish pages with underlines and, you know, marker highlights.

00:33:12.920 --> 00:33:18.920
[Guest]: That's all people are going to go, oh wow, that's a very good. He is quoting sources. So, that's true.

00:33:18.920 --> 00:33:26.920
[Guest]: Now, with the Aryan migration theory for that matter, it's okay. It's still a work in progress.

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:30.920
[Guest]: People are still studying the Aryans. It's not that everything is settled.

00:33:30.920 --> 00:33:34.920
[Guest]: But so far, there are common sense evidences, pieces of evidence.

00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:40.920
[Guest]: Like Ramayana and Mahabharata, these epics, they were written during the Vedic period.

00:33:40.920 --> 00:33:44.920
[Guest]: During the post Vedic period, sorry, by the Aryan authors.

00:33:44.920 --> 00:33:52.920
[Guest]: And they have very clear mentions of wheels for that matter, raths, chariots.

00:33:52.920 --> 00:33:58.920
[Guest]: Now, these chariots are supposed to be drawn by horses and those chariots are supposed to have wheels with spokes in them.

00:33:58.920 --> 00:34:06.920
[Guest]: In fact, spoke is such a prominent feature of those chariots that there is a story, there is a part in Ramayana where, I think,

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:16.920
[Guest]: one of Dasaratha's wives, she does something, there is a battle in which one of the spokes of Dasaratha's chariot breaks down

00:34:16.920 --> 00:34:22.920
[Guest]: and then she just puts in her hand to make the rath stable and something like that happens.

00:34:22.920 --> 00:34:28.920
[Guest]: And that's how she got to have an upper hand when it came to sending Rama out of the court.

00:34:28.920 --> 00:34:36.920
[Guest]: Now, so, the spokes are supposed to be there, the horses are supposed to be there and till date in none of the excavations,

00:34:36.920 --> 00:34:42.920
[Guest]: none of the sites, be it Sonali or Mehragarh or whatever sites we have till date,

00:34:42.920 --> 00:34:51.920
[Guest]: spoked chariots have not been found. You have found pottery, you have found animals, you have found animal bones and fossils and everything.

00:34:51.920 --> 00:34:54.920
[Guest]: You have not found horses. There are no horses in Sonali.

00:34:54.920 --> 00:35:03.920
[Guest]: So, if the Aryans were that old, like older than Indus Valley Civilization and they were native to India,

00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:09.920
[Guest]: and Sonali is as old as Indus Valley Civilization, there should be at least one horse fossil. Till date, none.

00:35:09.920 --> 00:35:14.920
[Guest]: Tomorrow, if we do find one, then yes, the theory might develop into something else.

00:35:14.920 --> 00:35:21.920
[Guest]: But so far, there is simply no evidence. So, yeah, just because it doesn't suit one's narrative, facts don't change.

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:25.920
[Guest]: And then, of course, like Peggy Mohan says, there are linguistic evidences.

00:35:25.920 --> 00:35:30.920
[Guest]: Why, you know, there are retroflex consonants in the Indian language.

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:38.920
[Guest]: If Aryans went from India to other countries, why is retroflex just exclusive to Indian languages?

00:35:38.920 --> 00:35:47.920
[Guest]: There is no retroflex in European languages, not even in languages that are very linguistically similar to Indian languages like Russian and stuff.

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:53.920
[Guest]: And then, of course, genetics. You can fight with everything. You can't fight with genetics.

00:35:53.920 --> 00:36:00.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, just to sort of elaborate for those listeners who may not have read Peggy's book or heard my episode with her,

00:36:00.920 --> 00:36:06.920
[Amit Varma]: what this whole thing about retroflex sounds is, take the words D-A-A-N-T.

00:36:06.920 --> 00:36:12.920
[Amit Varma]: You can now pronounce it D-A-A-N-T to mean teeth or you can pronounce it D-A-A-N-T to mean a scolding.

00:36:12.920 --> 00:36:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And when you're pronouncing it D-A-N-T, the D and the T, they are retroflex. The tongue is hitting the back of your mouth.

00:36:18.920 --> 00:36:27.920
[Amit Varma]: And those kind of sounds do not exist in any of the other languages which have descended from, you know, the whole Aryan family,

00:36:27.920 --> 00:36:31.920
[Amit Varma]: Proto-Indo-European, as it were, from which Sanskrit came.

00:36:31.920 --> 00:36:39.920
[Amit Varma]: So the thing is, as those languages, as those people made their way down over here, those retroflex sounds got into the language.

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:46.920
[Amit Varma]: And that is kind of unique. And that also tells you that it is not that European languages evolved from Sanskrit, as some people might claim,

00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:56.920
[Amit Varma]: but that Sanskrit was this incredibly rich offshoot of those languages, which also incorporated elements of the local languages, such as these retroflex sounds.

00:36:56.920 --> 00:37:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Peggy's book has just a lot more really rich dope on this and all of that.

00:37:01.920 --> 00:37:07.920
[Amit Varma]: And for those of my listeners who want to understand what do I mean by genetic evidence for something that happened in history,

00:37:07.920 --> 00:37:13.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, please listen to my episode with Tony Joseph or even better, read his book, which I think Early Indians is out in this new edition, right?

00:37:13.920 --> 00:37:18.920
[Amit Varma]: Which has been updated. I think it's just out. I'll link to the new edition as well.

00:37:18.920 --> 00:37:26.920
[Amit Varma]: So kind of, it's remarkable how far the science progresses. And, you know, regarding these contestations,

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:30.920
[Amit Varma]: this contestation, you can say, haan, theek hai, thousands of years old. How do we know?

00:37:30.920 --> 00:37:35.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, there's no writing from that period or anything. So, you know, you can dispute this.

00:37:35.920 --> 00:37:41.920
[Amit Varma]: But even recent historical events, it seems to me, are disputed with the same kind of vigor.

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:46.920
[Amit Varma]: For example, the Babri-Malchit demolition. Now, I did an episode with Vinay Sitapati,

00:37:46.920 --> 00:37:55.920
[Amit Varma]: who wrote that excellent book on the BJP before Modi, Jugalbandi. And his case was that Vajpayee-Advani, they were all taken unaware by it.

00:37:55.920 --> 00:38:01.920
[Amit Varma]: One criticism of the book is that his sources for that were people who were already, you know, amenable to that point of view.

00:38:01.920 --> 00:38:07.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, I have heard different points of view with different sets of evidences, which are contradictory.

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:11.920
[Amit Varma]: So, I can basically believe whatever I want and there will be evidence for that.

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:19.920
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, in the 2002 riots, was Modi culpable or was he merely incompetent? And he didn't know. He was blindsided by them.

00:38:19.920 --> 00:38:25.920
[Amit Varma]: I have heard really convincing arguments with apparently convincing evidence from both sides.

00:38:25.920 --> 00:38:34.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, now the thing is that if you are a neutral, if you're not a historian, if you haven't really gone deep into these issues, what the hell do you do?

00:38:34.920 --> 00:38:38.920
[Amit Varma]: If you've already chosen your political side, you will obviously believe that version.

00:38:38.920 --> 00:38:43.920
[Amit Varma]: And if you haven't chosen your political side, you will just shrug your shoulder and say, yeah, like whatever.

00:38:43.920 --> 00:38:50.920
[Guest]: Yeah, it's not always necessary. That's the first thing I always tell everyone and everyone I know and I talk to.

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:55.920
[Guest]: And that's something even I follow. We don't always need to have an opinion.

00:38:55.920 --> 00:39:00.920
[Guest]: Like, if you approach history from a place of opinion, there are two ways you can study history.

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:03.920
[Guest]: A. To learn and B. To validate.

00:39:03.920 --> 00:39:12.920
[Guest]: So, if you approach history as a search for validation, then you're not getting anywhere.

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:18.920
[Guest]: You'll just get the validation you need, but you'll not be getting anywhere close to what exactly happened.

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:28.920
[Guest]: Now, if you're looking for facts, if you're coming from a place of genuine curiosity, you may or may not discover what you're looking for.

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:37.920
[Guest]: I'm saying this right off the bat because, like you said, there are very convincing evidences on both sides of the argument.

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:49.920
[Guest]: And not just about, you know, contentious topics like Modi and 2002 and Babri Masjid, but everything, everything, even world history, like history is even right now.

00:39:49.920 --> 00:39:57.920
[Guest]: There are books written to exonerate Modi on how he handled COVID.

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:05.920
[Guest]: There are books written. There is a book, I believe, on how Muslims triggered the Delhi riots of last year.

00:40:05.920 --> 00:40:10.920
[Guest]: And then there are, of course, books on how Delhi riots were a state-sponsored program and stuff.

00:40:10.920 --> 00:40:19.920
[Guest]: So, 30 years down the line, people are going to get both the books and they will have no choice but to pick sides, whatever you want to believe.

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:24.920
[Guest]: Now, what I believe is, I don't need to have an opinion on everything.

00:40:24.920 --> 00:40:34.920
[Guest]: First thing, follow Occam's razor. Occam's razor is, you know, where the simplest thing, the most likely thing is likely the truth.

00:40:34.920 --> 00:40:42.920
[Guest]: Now, in the case of 2002, OK, fine, I don't know.

00:40:42.920 --> 00:40:46.920
[Guest]: Modi did get a clean chit, right? So, I don't know if he was culpable.

00:40:46.920 --> 00:40:53.920
[Guest]: But at the same time, Modi has a history of Islamophobic activities or at least utterances, right?

00:40:53.920 --> 00:41:02.920
[Guest]: Forget about what he did until 2002, but after 2002, after 2014, he has been as Islamophobic as it gets, his entire ecosystem.

00:41:02.920 --> 00:41:07.920
[Guest]: So, based on that, is it likely? Sometimes things are so fuzzy, you have to just go with the word likely.

00:41:07.920 --> 00:41:12.920
[Guest]: Is it likely that Modi was culpable? Seems so to me.

00:41:12.920 --> 00:41:19.920
[Guest]: But was he? I would not be sure. I would not be sure because I don't have concrete evidence of that.

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:23.920
[Guest]: The only thing I can rely on is the Supreme Court for better or for worse.

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:27.920
[Guest]: And the Supreme Court did, not Supreme Court, sorry, the legal system in general.

00:41:27.920 --> 00:41:31.920
[Guest]: And the legal system gave him a clean chit which is what I have to go by

00:41:31.920 --> 00:41:40.920
[Guest]: because if I start doubting that, then there is a whole lot of judgments that are in my ideology's favor, so to say.

00:41:40.920 --> 00:41:45.920
[Guest]: And I'll have to doubt them also, right? So, it's up to you.

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:49.920
[Guest]: For me, the thing is, 2002 shouldn't have happened.

00:41:49.920 --> 00:42:00.920
[Guest]: And we should ensure that these kinds of confusions do not flare up into situations where hundreds of people have to lose their lives and livelihood.

00:42:00.920 --> 00:42:03.920
[Guest]: That's a lesson 2002 gives us.

00:42:03.920 --> 00:42:07.920
[Guest]: Now, whether you want to feel proud of it or ashamed of it, it's up to you.

00:42:07.920 --> 00:42:10.920
[Guest]: I don't feel either of the emotions from that.

00:42:10.920 --> 00:42:15.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, that's a good tangential point that this whole notion of pride just kind of baffles me

00:42:15.920 --> 00:42:18.920
[Amit Varma]: that if someone wins an Olympic gold for India, for example,

00:42:18.920 --> 00:42:23.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm supposed to feel proud or I'm supposed to feel ashamed if something really reprehensible happens somewhere.

00:42:23.920 --> 00:42:31.920
[Amit Varma]: And my sense of it is that, one, I don't think I'll feel either proud or ashamed unless it has something to do with my personal actions.

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:37.920
[Amit Varma]: And even there, so much of what I do is just not as much in my control as I think it is,

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:40.920
[Amit Varma]: that I don't even know if those emotions are appropriate there.

00:42:40.920 --> 00:42:46.920
[Amit Varma]: But certainly this whole sort of notion of national pride and all that is a little bizarre.

00:42:46.920 --> 00:42:55.920
[Amit Varma]: The other sort of aspect is that certain historical narratives, they become almost in a sense tied to an ideology

00:42:55.920 --> 00:43:01.920
[Amit Varma]: in such a way that if you revisit the history, you are automatically questioning the ideology.

00:43:01.920 --> 00:43:05.920
[Amit Varma]: And that then becomes a political question in a sense.

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:11.920
[Amit Varma]: Part of it is, of course, what Kapil Kamireddy in a past episode with me and Manu Pillay in his recent episode also alluded to it,

00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:19.920
[Amit Varma]: is some of the whitewashing by our historians after independence of stuff that had happened under the Mughals and all of that

00:43:19.920 --> 00:43:23.920
[Amit Varma]: because they didn't want communal violence to flare up in modern India.

00:43:23.920 --> 00:43:29.920
[Amit Varma]: So for perhaps, you know, well-intentioned reasons, they did an alighting of certain aspects of history,

00:43:29.920 --> 00:43:34.920
[Amit Varma]: which according to Kapil, Kapil's thesis was that you can't do this, that it will eventually catch up with you,

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:38.920
[Amit Varma]: that people will resent it if you're sort of whitewashing this.

00:43:38.920 --> 00:43:45.920
[Amit Varma]: But that notion of, you know, Akbar, great enlightened emperor, that is almost liberal dogma now.

00:43:45.920 --> 00:43:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And equally, it is almost a dogma of the right wing that Aurangzeb was all bad.

00:43:49.920 --> 00:43:54.920
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, all of them contain multitudes and all these things are true.

00:43:54.920 --> 00:44:00.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, Aurangzeb did do a lot of ghastly things and Akbar was a very interesting guy who tried some pretty funky experiments.

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:04.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, I was reminded of this recently when, you know, in the last few years,

00:44:04.920 --> 00:44:10.920
[Amit Varma]: there's this narrative going on about how Churchill was responsible for the Bengal famine of 42 or 43 or whatever,

00:44:10.920 --> 00:44:12.920
[Amit Varma]: started with a book Madhuri Shri Mukherjee wrote.

00:44:12.920 --> 00:44:16.920
[Amit Varma]: So I read the book and I'm like, my God, Churchill was such a monster.

00:44:16.920 --> 00:44:20.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's my default thing. And I said, I have to find out more.

00:44:20.920 --> 00:44:24.920
[Amit Varma]: And then I dug deeper, including in some of these cabinet papers that she mentioned

00:44:24.920 --> 00:44:28.920
[Amit Varma]: and actually went into some of her sources, read other biographies of the period.

00:44:28.920 --> 00:44:32.920
[Amit Varma]: And at the end of it, I realized that what she had essentially done was she had cherry-picked evidence

00:44:32.920 --> 00:44:38.920
[Amit Varma]: that not only was Churchill not responsible for the Bengal famine, in my view, I mean, this can be argued forever.

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:44.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, Amartya Sen also disputed Madhuri Shri Mukherjee on another aspect of what she wrote in that particular book.

00:44:44.920 --> 00:44:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, if I find, I vaguely remember a couple of other scholarly pieces that looked into it.

00:44:49.920 --> 00:44:55.920
[Amit Varma]: But this narrative that Churchill was evil and caused the Bengal famine has almost become a matter of dogma,

00:44:55.920 --> 00:45:01.920
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that I mentioned to somebody the other day that I think she cherry-picked her evidence in terms of the letters that he wrote.

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:05.920
[Amit Varma]: She didn't quote from other letters where he's saying something completely different.

00:45:05.920 --> 00:45:10.920
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Andrew Roberts wrote a million-word biography of Churchill, a magisterial book,

00:45:10.920 --> 00:45:16.920
[Amit Varma]: where he looks at, you know, Watson or Olive Shades of Grey, where he even kind of makes a case that

00:45:16.920 --> 00:45:19.920
[Amit Varma]: if Churchill wasn't there, more people might have died, you know.

00:45:19.920 --> 00:45:26.920
[Amit Varma]: And there's just so many nuances that, you know, you're blaming him for not sending ships with food grains or whatever,

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:31.920
[Amit Varma]: when the point is that, you know, his ships were getting sunk, I think, at a crazy rate within the ocean.

00:45:31.920 --> 00:45:36.920
[Amit Varma]: There was a danger of losing the war. There were all these other considerations that came into play.

00:45:36.920 --> 00:45:40.920
[Amit Varma]: Which is not to say, again, lest people misinterpret it as a defense of Churchill.

00:45:40.920 --> 00:45:45.920
[Amit Varma]: It's not to say that he wasn't racist. Of course, he was racist. Of course, he hated Indians.

00:45:45.920 --> 00:45:51.920
[Amit Varma]: Of course, he held us brown-skinned natives in contempt. And of course, he was also a great man

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:56.920
[Amit Varma]: and perhaps saved the Western world with the kind of attitude he took. And these multitudes exist.

00:45:56.920 --> 00:46:04.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I just thought of that as an example of where something that should be open to dispute,

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:09.920
[Amit Varma]: that did this happen or not, somehow is politically not open to dispute.

00:46:09.920 --> 00:46:14.920
[Amit Varma]: You become evil if you question it. Because it is part of the dogma that, yeah, Churchill killed so many Bengalis.

00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And I'm half Bengali, by the way. When I first read the book, I thought, these are, he's killing my people, bastard.

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:21.920
[Amit Varma]: But actually not so, if you dig a little deeper.

00:46:21.920 --> 00:46:27.920
[Guest]: Of course, we admit that nobody can be entirely evil or entirely bad, unless you're talking about somebody like Hitler.

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:35.920
[Guest]: By the way, even somebody like Hitler has his grace. But that's a separate conversation.

00:46:35.920 --> 00:46:37.920
[Amit Varma]: He was vegetarian.

00:46:37.920 --> 00:46:44.920
[Guest]: It's the kind of thing where, okay, fine. So, what if he beats his wife? He files his taxes on time.

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:51.920
[Guest]: You've heard that joke, right? So, Hitler was the first person to introduce animal cruelty laws in all of Europe.

00:46:51.920 --> 00:46:55.920
[Guest]: Hitler is the first person who ended human zoos.

00:46:55.920 --> 00:47:09.920
[Guest]: There used to be this idea, this absolutely atrocious idea of putting people in theme park-like situations

00:47:09.920 --> 00:47:15.920
[Guest]: where you have these Negroes from America brought in, you know, slave girls and kids and guys.

00:47:15.920 --> 00:47:21.920
[Guest]: And they are put in pens, pig pens, and white visitors come and see them.

00:47:21.920 --> 00:47:25.920
[Guest]: And it was more like an anthropological exercise.

00:47:25.920 --> 00:47:30.920
[Guest]: You see how tribals live in Africa and what they look like and how they talk, how they behave.

00:47:30.920 --> 00:47:32.920
[Guest]: So, these were human zoos.

00:47:32.920 --> 00:47:39.920
[Guest]: And Hitler, as racist as he was, he's the person who abolished human zoos.

00:47:39.920 --> 00:47:44.920
[Guest]: What was his thinking behind that? How he approached it? I have no idea.

00:47:44.920 --> 00:47:47.920
[Guest]: We can't get into his mind. But we know he did that.

00:47:47.920 --> 00:47:50.920
[Guest]: Then, of course, the animal cruelty laws.

00:47:50.920 --> 00:47:54.920
[Guest]: He's the first person who introduced the idea of paid vacations in Germany

00:47:54.920 --> 00:47:59.920
[Guest]: because he wanted all the German working class people to have some, you know, quality of life

00:47:59.920 --> 00:48:02.920
[Guest]: and so that they are more patriotic. Of course, he had his reasons.

00:48:02.920 --> 00:48:04.920
[Guest]: He wanted loyalty of the people to the Reich.

00:48:04.920 --> 00:48:12.920
[Guest]: And he started the policy of having compulsory annual vacation for German workers.

00:48:12.920 --> 00:48:14.920
[Guest]: Gave them radios so that they are aware of what's happening.

00:48:14.920 --> 00:48:19.920
[Guest]: Again, he had his own agenda there because through the radios he could, you know,

00:48:19.920 --> 00:48:22.920
[Guest]: he literally had a propaganda minister.

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:25.920
[Guest]: So, you can imagine why he would distribute free radios.

00:48:25.920 --> 00:48:30.920
[Guest]: But there are things he did which cannot be called evil.

00:48:30.920 --> 00:48:35.920
[Guest]: And again, this is not just. We have to continuously keep captioning ourselves, you know.

00:48:35.920 --> 00:48:38.920
[Guest]: This is not a justification of Churchill or justification for Hitler.

00:48:38.920 --> 00:48:41.920
[Guest]: But these things happen. You can't wish them away.

00:48:41.920 --> 00:48:46.920
[Guest]: You cannot pin this on one political ideology or the other.

00:48:46.920 --> 00:48:50.920
[Guest]: It's just how the world has shaped over the past.

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:55.920
[Guest]: And this is not a seven year or ten years thing.

00:48:55.920 --> 00:48:58.920
[Guest]: The buildup is more than half a century old.

00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:01.920
[Guest]: It's been in the works since independence.

00:49:01.920 --> 00:49:05.920
[Guest]: And yes, it's true. Things have been whitewashed.

00:49:05.920 --> 00:49:10.920
[Guest]: History has been colored with agenda ever since independence.

00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:13.920
[Guest]: The Mughal history has been tampered with.

00:49:13.920 --> 00:49:17.920
[Guest]: And sooner or later, yes, it has to come out.

00:49:17.920 --> 00:49:22.920
[Guest]: The way the world is opening up with every kind of opinion and resources

00:49:22.920 --> 00:49:27.920
[Guest]: and things are becoming approachable to everyone

00:49:27.920 --> 00:49:32.920
[Guest]: regardless of where they stand in the society or educational hierarchy.

00:49:32.920 --> 00:49:35.920
[Guest]: So, people would find out.

00:49:35.920 --> 00:49:39.920
[Guest]: Maybe back in the 90s, back in the 50s and 60s,

00:49:39.920 --> 00:49:43.920
[Guest]: nobody would have seen. Nobody would have seen this coming.

00:49:43.920 --> 00:49:46.920
[Guest]: There would come a time where everything will be exposed.

00:49:46.920 --> 00:49:49.920
[Guest]: So, fine, they might have come from a good place,

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:53.920
[Guest]: like you said, to maintain communal harmony.

00:49:53.920 --> 00:49:56.920
[Guest]: That was the priority of the time.

00:49:56.920 --> 00:50:02.920
[Guest]: But eventually, you are just postponing the problems.

00:50:02.920 --> 00:50:05.920
[Guest]: You are not fixing them. You are postponing them.

00:50:05.920 --> 00:50:08.920
[Guest]: Because the communal disharmony that would have happened in the 50s

00:50:08.920 --> 00:50:12.920
[Guest]: had you opened up the atrocities of the Mughals,

00:50:12.920 --> 00:50:16.920
[Guest]: that did not happen then. It's happening now in 2021.

00:50:16.920 --> 00:50:21.920
[Guest]: Nobody from that time is alive now to see the consequences of what they wrote.

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:23.920
[Guest]: But it happened.

00:50:23.920 --> 00:50:28.920
[Guest]: And this happens when you are emotional about characters.

00:50:28.920 --> 00:50:32.920
[Guest]: This whole thing is because one side is emotional about the Mughals

00:50:32.920 --> 00:50:36.920
[Guest]: and the other side is emotional about, say, the Sikhs and the Hindus.

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:39.920
[Guest]: Everybody is beholden to their favourite characters.

00:50:39.920 --> 00:50:42.920
[Guest]: You have to understand that the people you are emotional about are real people.

00:50:42.920 --> 00:50:45.920
[Guest]: This is not Lord of the Rings or Harry Potter.

00:50:45.920 --> 00:50:49.920
[Guest]: They were who they were. They cannot be changed.

00:50:49.920 --> 00:50:52.920
[Guest]: Aurangzeb did what he did. Tipu Sultan did what he did.

00:50:52.920 --> 00:50:54.920
[Guest]: You can't change it just because you feel nice for them.

00:50:54.920 --> 00:50:57.920
[Guest]: Just because you identify with them.

00:50:57.920 --> 00:51:00.920
[Guest]: And why you identify with them? Because he was Muslim and I am also Muslim.

00:51:00.920 --> 00:51:03.920
[Guest]: Or maybe I am a liberal and I feel for Muslims, which is good.

00:51:03.920 --> 00:51:06.920
[Guest]: You should feel for... I mean, why Muslim? You should feel for everyone.

00:51:06.920 --> 00:51:11.920
[Guest]: But this association, this identification by association

00:51:11.920 --> 00:51:14.920
[Guest]: is what's ruining history for everyone, both left and right.

00:51:14.920 --> 00:51:17.920
[Guest]: For all you know, whatever is happening,

00:51:17.920 --> 00:51:20.920
[Guest]: the WhatsApp forwards and the right-wing rewriting of history,

00:51:20.920 --> 00:51:24.920
[Guest]: why can't I call this a reprisal of sorts?

00:51:24.920 --> 00:51:27.920
[Guest]: The voices have been suppressed for far too long.

00:51:27.920 --> 00:51:30.920
[Guest]: There were intellectual barriers. Now those barriers are gone.

00:51:30.920 --> 00:51:34.920
[Guest]: Now a Panipuriwala can have an opinion and it can be broadcast.

00:51:34.920 --> 00:51:37.920
[Guest]: So he is doing it.

00:51:37.920 --> 00:51:40.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's fascinating. And a bunch of tangential thoughts you mentioned

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:43.920
[Amit Varma]: about how human zoos, people kept in cages.

00:51:43.920 --> 00:51:46.920
[Amit Varma]: And I remember this post I wrote in 2007,

00:51:46.920 --> 00:51:49.920
[Amit Varma]: which I've just dug out, which has a thought which,

00:51:49.920 --> 00:51:52.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, might be relevant to what's happening around us.

00:51:52.920 --> 00:51:55.920
[Amit Varma]: And the post began with something that a blogger had written about

00:51:55.920 --> 00:51:58.920
[Amit Varma]: this guy called Ota Benga. And Ota Benga was a pygmy

00:51:58.920 --> 00:52:01.920
[Amit Varma]: from the Belgian Congo. And he was taken to the US.

00:52:01.920 --> 00:52:04.920
[Amit Varma]: And he was displayed at the Bronx Zoo

00:52:04.920 --> 00:52:07.920
[Amit Varma]: in a cage, which he shared with an orangutan.

00:52:07.920 --> 00:52:10.920
[Amit Varma]: And it was meant to show the different stages of evolution.

00:52:10.920 --> 00:52:14.920
[Amit Varma]: So you have orangutan and you have an African pygmy.

00:52:14.920 --> 00:52:17.920
[Amit Varma]: And he had teeth, which was slightly odd because it was a particular

00:52:17.920 --> 00:52:20.920
[Amit Varma]: tradition of cosmetic dentistry that his tribe followed.

00:52:20.920 --> 00:52:23.920
[Amit Varma]: But the narrative that his captors built was that

00:52:23.920 --> 00:52:26.920
[Amit Varma]: this is a sign of cannibalism. So to spread that narrative

00:52:26.920 --> 00:52:29.920
[Amit Varma]: among the people who came to the zoo, they scattered bones in the cage.

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:32.920
[Amit Varma]: Right. Now, thinking of it today,

00:52:32.920 --> 00:52:35.920
[Amit Varma]: we are utterly aghast. But back in the day,

00:52:35.920 --> 00:52:38.920
[Amit Varma]: obviously, this was considered normal because people went to the zoo.

00:52:38.920 --> 00:52:41.920
[Amit Varma]: Like we might go to the zoo today and say, let's go

00:52:41.920 --> 00:52:44.920
[Amit Varma]: and look at some panthers and giraffes and whatever.

00:52:44.920 --> 00:52:47.920
[Amit Varma]: In a similar sense, let's go look at some pygmies.

00:52:47.920 --> 00:52:50.920
[Amit Varma]: And I had used this example in the post to

00:52:50.920 --> 00:52:53.920
[Amit Varma]: talk about something called the expanding circle.

00:52:53.920 --> 00:52:56.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, the expanding circle is a concept created by the philosopher

00:52:56.920 --> 00:52:59.920
[Amit Varma]: W.E.H. Leckie, coined by the philosopher in his book

00:52:59.920 --> 00:53:02.920
[Amit Varma]: A History of European Morals. And I think it's still relevant to

00:53:02.920 --> 00:53:05.920
[Amit Varma]: how we think about the world today in the sense that Leckie's point

00:53:05.920 --> 00:53:08.920
[Amit Varma]: was that we are wired to have a circle

00:53:08.920 --> 00:53:11.920
[Amit Varma]: of people we consider our people and everybody outside

00:53:11.920 --> 00:53:14.920
[Amit Varma]: that is the other. So for all practical purposes,

00:53:14.920 --> 00:53:17.920
[Amit Varma]: everybody outside that circle of people, they can die.

00:53:17.920 --> 00:53:20.920
[Amit Varma]: We can do unspeakable things to them. It doesn't matter.

00:53:20.920 --> 00:53:23.920
[Amit Varma]: They are the other. They are like animals are to us today. It doesn't matter.

00:53:23.920 --> 00:53:26.920
[Amit Varma]: It never happens. So and initially his point was that

00:53:26.920 --> 00:53:29.920
[Amit Varma]: our circle is small. It's our family. It's our tribe and so on.

00:53:29.920 --> 00:53:32.920
[Amit Varma]: And the great thing about human civilization

00:53:32.920 --> 00:53:35.920
[Amit Varma]: is that the circle expands so that the

00:53:35.920 --> 00:53:38.920
[Amit Varma]: people who are worthy of our moral consideration,

00:53:38.920 --> 00:53:41.920
[Amit Varma]: they expand from our tribe to perhaps our region to

00:53:41.920 --> 00:53:44.920
[Amit Varma]: our nation state as it were till it

00:53:44.920 --> 00:53:47.920
[Amit Varma]: eventually engulfs all of humanity or should

00:53:47.920 --> 00:53:50.920
[Amit Varma]: engulf all of humanity. And in fact, the philosopher,

00:53:50.920 --> 00:53:53.920
[Amit Varma]: the utilitarian philosopher Peter Singer wrote a book

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:56.920
[Amit Varma]: about it in the late 1970s. I was about to say

00:53:56.920 --> 00:53:59.920
[Amit Varma]: recent book till I realized it's in the 70s.

00:53:59.920 --> 00:54:02.920
[Amit Varma]: But it feels recent to me given my vintage.

00:54:02.920 --> 00:54:05.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm also in my 40s like you. Where he wrote a book called

00:54:05.920 --> 00:54:08.920
[Amit Varma]: The Expanding Circle and Singer's argument. Singer used to fight

00:54:08.920 --> 00:54:11.920
[Amit Varma]: for animal liberation as it were. That's the title of another book of his.

00:54:11.920 --> 00:54:14.920
[Amit Varma]: And Singer's argument was that this circle will expand

00:54:14.920 --> 00:54:17.920
[Amit Varma]: to include animals. So in the same way that

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:20.920
[Amit Varma]: you and I can be aghast today thinking about

00:54:20.920 --> 00:54:23.920
[Amit Varma]: the African black man who was exhibited in a cage

00:54:23.920 --> 00:54:26.920
[Amit Varma]: somewhere, 150 years down the line

00:54:26.920 --> 00:54:29.920
[Amit Varma]: people could be aghast that we killed animals to eat them.

00:54:29.920 --> 00:54:32.920
[Amit Varma]: Of course. Yeah. And my therefore,

00:54:32.920 --> 00:54:35.920
[Amit Varma]: musing therefore is that

00:54:35.920 --> 00:54:38.920
[Amit Varma]: in a sense all the cruelty that we commit on each other,

00:54:38.920 --> 00:54:41.920
[Amit Varma]: not all the cruelty but a lot of the cruelty we commit on

00:54:41.920 --> 00:54:44.920
[Amit Varma]: each other is because our circle hasn't

00:54:44.920 --> 00:54:47.920
[Amit Varma]: actually expanded that much. That there are people who are outside

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:50.920
[Amit Varma]: our circle and if we do something to them, we don't

00:54:50.920 --> 00:54:53.920
[Amit Varma]: consider them human. We consider them sub-human. They're not worthy of

00:54:53.920 --> 00:54:56.920
[Amit Varma]: a moral consideration. So for example, you know a

00:54:56.920 --> 00:54:59.920
[Amit Varma]: Brahmin who for example will slaughter a Dalit for drinking from

00:54:59.920 --> 00:55:02.920
[Amit Varma]: his well or a bunch of Hindus who will slaughter some

00:55:02.920 --> 00:55:05.920
[Amit Varma]: Muslims they see who they feel might be transporting

00:55:05.920 --> 00:55:08.920
[Amit Varma]: beef or you know we are recording this a couple of

00:55:08.920 --> 00:55:11.920
[Amit Varma]: days after the Singhu death where this guy's hand was chopped off by

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:14.920
[Amit Varma]: Nihang Sikhs and he was apparently a Dalit Sikh

00:55:14.920 --> 00:55:17.920
[Amit Varma]: and he was accused of you know desecrating the holy book but whatever

00:55:17.920 --> 00:55:20.920
[Amit Varma]: his hand was chopped off. He was basically tortured to death and

00:55:20.920 --> 00:55:23.920
[Amit Varma]: his body was hung up and they continued defending it, the people who killed him.

00:55:23.920 --> 00:55:26.920
[Amit Varma]: They continued defending it as if he wasn't human.

00:55:26.920 --> 00:55:29.920
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. And this is kind of what worries me

00:55:29.920 --> 00:55:32.920
[Amit Varma]: that those of us who are more

00:55:32.920 --> 00:55:35.920
[Amit Varma]: who are English speaking elites who might have the influence of the

00:55:35.920 --> 00:55:38.920
[Amit Varma]: enlightenment on them for example or who have this western liberal

00:55:38.920 --> 00:55:41.920
[Amit Varma]: sort of way of looking at things might assume that

00:55:41.920 --> 00:55:44.920
[Amit Varma]: everyone's circle has expanded and therefore everyone should be

00:55:44.920 --> 00:55:47.920
[Amit Varma]: horrified at such murders or lynching or whatever.

00:55:47.920 --> 00:55:50.920
[Amit Varma]: But the truth is that there are so many intersecting circles

00:55:50.920 --> 00:55:53.920
[Amit Varma]: all around us and it's not really like that.

00:55:53.920 --> 00:55:56.920
[Guest]: I believe the number of circles have increased.

00:55:56.920 --> 00:55:59.920
[Guest]: I mean once upon a time but then yeah all said and done

00:55:59.920 --> 00:56:02.920
[Guest]: I would still preamble all of this whatever I am going to say

00:56:02.920 --> 00:56:05.920
[Guest]: with one very clear thought

00:56:05.920 --> 00:56:08.920
[Guest]: unambiguous not to contest that

00:56:08.920 --> 00:56:11.920
[Guest]: we are living in far better times than

00:56:11.920 --> 00:56:14.920
[Guest]: ever before in history. So that is

00:56:14.920 --> 00:56:17.920
[Guest]: unassailable. Now

00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:20.920
[Guest]: having said that the circles

00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:23.920
[Guest]: are certainly expanding. There is no two ways

00:56:23.920 --> 00:56:26.920
[Guest]: about it. I mean that's how we are living in better times than before.

00:56:26.920 --> 00:56:29.920
[Guest]: But the number of circles

00:56:29.920 --> 00:56:32.920
[Guest]: is increasing as well. Like earlier

00:56:32.920 --> 00:56:35.920
[Guest]: it was just my race and then nation state and then

00:56:35.920 --> 00:56:38.920
[Guest]: you know my species and those kind of things.

00:56:38.920 --> 00:56:41.920
[Guest]: Now we are creating a new circle

00:56:41.920 --> 00:56:44.920
[Guest]: every day every month like you know

00:56:44.920 --> 00:56:47.920
[Guest]: we have circles based on orientation. We have circles

00:56:47.920 --> 00:56:50.920
[Guest]: based on gender. We have circles based on

00:56:50.920 --> 00:56:53.920
[Guest]: socio-economic parameters.

00:56:53.920 --> 00:56:56.920
[Guest]: We have circles based on every conceivable box

00:56:56.920 --> 00:56:59.920
[Guest]: a person can be put in.

00:56:59.920 --> 00:57:02.920
[Guest]: You can call me a cishet

00:57:02.920 --> 00:57:05.920
[Guest]: upper class Hindu. Earlier it used to be

00:57:05.920 --> 00:57:08.920
[Guest]: upper caste Hindu. You are a lower caste. You are a Dalit

00:57:08.920 --> 00:57:11.920
[Amit Varma]: you are an upper caste. Now you have upper class.

00:57:11.920 --> 00:57:14.920
[Amit Varma]: I thought cishet is pretty much the worst insult

00:57:14.920 --> 00:57:17.920
[Guest]: that you can get.

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:20.920
[Guest]: There are so many circles so many tags so many names

00:57:20.920 --> 00:57:23.920
[Guest]: that it's become very hard. I mean at one point

00:57:23.920 --> 00:57:26.920
[Guest]: you just give up. You give up trying to figure out

00:57:26.920 --> 00:57:29.920
[Guest]: what the hierarchy looks like because there is no hierarchy.

00:57:29.920 --> 00:57:32.920
[Guest]: There are so many intersections like in the

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:35.920
[Guest]: single border thing. Now what do you do? Like I was

00:57:35.920 --> 00:57:38.920
[Guest]: telling you before lunch. How do you

00:57:38.920 --> 00:57:41.920
[Guest]: pick sides? Like if you have to pick sides

00:57:41.920 --> 00:57:44.920
[Guest]: based on ideological

00:57:44.920 --> 00:57:47.920
[Guest]: boxes that you subscribe to then

00:57:47.920 --> 00:57:50.920
[Guest]: the victim is a Dalit and

00:57:50.920 --> 00:57:53.920
[Guest]: the perpetrator is I don't know if Nihangs are upper caste

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:56.920
[Guest]: or whatever.

00:57:56.920 --> 00:57:59.920
[Guest]: So you feel bad for the victim but then at the same time

00:57:59.920 --> 00:58:02.920
[Guest]: you realize the perpetrator is a minority in India

00:58:02.920 --> 00:58:05.920
[Guest]: and minority not just

00:58:05.920 --> 00:58:08.920
[Guest]: minority but an oppressed minority because the Sikhs

00:58:08.920 --> 00:58:11.920
[Guest]: right now because of the farmer protest and everything the Sikhs

00:58:11.920 --> 00:58:14.920
[Guest]: are an oppressed minority. So how do you

00:58:14.920 --> 00:58:17.920
[Guest]: pick sides? So that's the peril of getting

00:58:17.920 --> 00:58:20.920
[Guest]: into identities and these circles.

00:58:20.920 --> 00:58:23.920
[Guest]: So we are inventing circles. Why we are doing

00:58:23.920 --> 00:58:26.920
[Guest]: that is for a philosopher or a

00:58:26.920 --> 00:58:29.920
[Guest]: think tank to come up with but I can

00:58:29.920 --> 00:58:32.920
[Guest]: only wager a guess that it's because

00:58:32.920 --> 00:58:35.920
[Guest]: as more and more people are

00:58:35.920 --> 00:58:38.920
[Guest]: getting a platform, a bullhorn to air their opinions

00:58:38.920 --> 00:58:41.920
[Guest]: of course everyone wants their own share

00:58:41.920 --> 00:58:44.920
[Guest]: of attention and even if it's a 5 minute

00:58:44.920 --> 00:58:47.920
[Guest]: limelight. So at some point

00:58:47.920 --> 00:58:50.920
[Guest]: it becomes fashionable to go against the grain

00:58:50.920 --> 00:58:53.920
[Guest]: so if the prevailing thought is that this is bad

00:58:53.920 --> 00:58:56.920
[Guest]: this shouldn't have happened then okay fine to justify the person who did it

00:58:56.920 --> 00:58:59.920
[Guest]: that becomes a contrarian view. It makes me some

00:58:59.920 --> 00:59:02.920
[Guest]: kind of a superstar for maybe 5 minutes.

00:59:02.920 --> 00:59:05.920
[Guest]: Oh wow this person is not just I don't want to be the

00:59:05.920 --> 00:59:08.920
[Guest]: sheep kind of mentality. So it happens.

00:59:08.920 --> 00:59:11.920
[Guest]: So in that flow I end up creating a new circle.

00:59:11.920 --> 00:59:14.920
[Guest]: I subscribe to XYZ ideology.

00:59:14.920 --> 00:59:17.920
[Guest]: This ideology didn't exist till now. I am creating it.

00:59:17.920 --> 00:59:20.920
[Guest]: It's happening. Now you mentioned

00:59:20.920 --> 00:59:23.920
[Guest]: this thing called TERF sometime back.

00:59:23.920 --> 00:59:26.920
[Guest]: So I never heard of this until

00:59:26.920 --> 00:59:29.920
[Guest]: a few weeks ago. Now tomorrow

00:59:29.920 --> 00:59:32.920
[Guest]: you will hear some other acronym. A new acronym is coming up everyday.

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:35.920
[Guest]: I believe the last time I checked LGBTQ

00:59:35.920 --> 00:59:38.920
[Guest]: had some more than 15-20

00:59:38.920 --> 00:59:41.920
[Guest]: letters and then a plus sign

00:59:41.920 --> 00:59:44.920
[Guest]: because then even they got tired.

00:59:44.920 --> 00:59:47.920
[Guest]: So it happens. We are creating new circles and that's the

00:59:47.920 --> 00:59:50.920
[Guest]: whole reason of conflicts because people don't see overlap.

00:59:50.920 --> 00:59:53.920
[Guest]: People just see okay we are different circles.

00:59:53.920 --> 00:59:56.920
[Amit Varma]: I would really say that the only part of this I would disagree with is

00:59:56.920 --> 00:59:59.920
[Amit Varma]: the fact that people don't want to be sheep. I think on the contrary

00:59:59.920 --> 01:00:02.920
[Amit Varma]: everybody does want to be a sheep in the sense that

01:00:02.920 --> 01:00:05.920
[Amit Varma]: I think social media has exacerbated this tendency where we

01:00:05.920 --> 01:00:08.920
[Amit Varma]: come online, we find an ideological tribe and

01:00:08.920 --> 01:00:11.920
[Amit Varma]: once we are within that ideological tribe we feel validated

01:00:11.920 --> 01:00:14.920
[Amit Varma]: and the way to get approval and more and more

01:00:14.920 --> 01:00:17.920
[Amit Varma]: validation from that tribe is to keep signalling our

01:00:17.920 --> 01:00:20.920
[Amit Varma]: virtue more and more loudly which inevitably is

01:00:20.920 --> 01:00:23.920
[Amit Varma]: a drive to the extremes because then you

01:00:23.920 --> 01:00:26.920
[Amit Varma]: keep shitting on the other side instead of engaging with them respectfully

01:00:26.920 --> 01:00:29.920
[Amit Varma]: as you should and treating them as people but instead

01:00:29.920 --> 01:00:32.920
[Amit Varma]: you never engage with arguments, you attack people and you

01:00:32.920 --> 01:00:35.920
[Amit Varma]: do purity tests for your own side where again

01:00:35.920 --> 01:00:38.920
[Amit Varma]: a drive to the extremes and one of the things and what we were

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:41.920
[Amit Varma]: kind of discussing during lunch and which I find very

01:00:41.920 --> 01:00:44.920
[Amit Varma]: distressing and which goes against everything that we discussed

01:00:44.920 --> 01:00:47.920
[Amit Varma]: about you know loving history means embracing

01:00:47.920 --> 01:00:50.920
[Amit Varma]: complexity is that all these tribal

01:00:50.920 --> 01:00:53.920
[Amit Varma]: instincts have led to the creation of these new ideological

01:00:53.920 --> 01:00:56.920
[Amit Varma]: tribes or even cults which are reductive

01:00:56.920 --> 01:00:59.920
[Amit Varma]: which are based on identity which are

01:00:59.920 --> 01:01:02.920
[Amit Varma]: reductive so you know whatever identity

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:05.920
[Amit Varma]: is assigned to you by the interlocutor

01:01:05.920 --> 01:01:08.920
[Amit Varma]: that's what you are, you are reduced to that, you are nothing

01:01:08.920 --> 01:01:11.920
[Amit Varma]: more than that so if someone calls me

01:01:11.920 --> 01:01:14.920
[Amit Varma]: a Siset Savanna for example and therefore I can't

01:01:14.920 --> 01:01:17.920
[Amit Varma]: you know I am by default evil and I should feel tremendous

01:01:17.920 --> 01:01:20.920
[Amit Varma]: guilt for other Siset Savannas in the past I have done

01:01:20.920 --> 01:01:23.920
[Amit Varma]: that reduces me to just that and it reduces me

01:01:23.920 --> 01:01:26.920
[Amit Varma]: also not just to an identity that I was born into

01:01:26.920 --> 01:01:29.920
[Amit Varma]: but into whatever the misdeeds

01:01:29.920 --> 01:01:32.920
[Amit Varma]: of you know my ancestors might have been which I have no control

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:35.920
[Amit Varma]: over and this also reduces people

01:01:35.920 --> 01:01:38.920
[Amit Varma]: to ideologies, to identities of victimhood

01:01:38.920 --> 01:01:41.920
[Amit Varma]: you know this John McWhorter has written

01:01:41.920 --> 01:01:44.920
[Amit Varma]: this excellent book called Woke Racism which is just out

01:01:44.920 --> 01:01:47.920
[Amit Varma]: so there is an interview of his I will link to where he

01:01:47.920 --> 01:01:50.920
[Amit Varma]: speaks about how he finds it so

01:01:50.920 --> 01:01:53.920
[Amit Varma]: condescending that you know black people are treated

01:01:53.920 --> 01:01:56.920
[Amit Varma]: as victims all the time that things happen to them

01:01:56.920 --> 01:01:59.920
[Amit Varma]: that they can't actually take their destiny into their

01:01:59.920 --> 01:02:02.920
[Amit Varma]: own hands and that's exactly as it should be and I

01:02:02.920 --> 01:02:05.920
[Amit Varma]: think just thinking in terms of identity reducing

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:08.920
[Amit Varma]: a person to a category it's a trap

01:02:08.920 --> 01:02:11.920
[Amit Varma]: not only like I don't care what you call me or you know

01:02:11.920 --> 01:02:14.920
[Amit Varma]: I can take those pejoratives

01:02:14.920 --> 01:02:17.920
[Amit Varma]: but it's a trap even for those people who

01:02:17.920 --> 01:02:20.920
[Amit Varma]: might be Dalit or who might be black or who might be

01:02:20.920 --> 01:02:23.920
[Amit Varma]: whatever category it is but you don't want to reduce

01:02:23.920 --> 01:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: them to the victimhood they are more than that what

01:02:26.920 --> 01:02:29.920
[Amit Varma]: has happened in their lives is more than oppression

01:02:29.920 --> 01:02:32.920
[Amit Varma]: they contain multitudes and to reduce them to that

01:02:32.920 --> 01:02:35.920
[Amit Varma]: to reduce a narrative to that is I think to do

01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:38.920
[Amit Varma]: pretty much the same thing as WhatsApp historians

01:02:38.920 --> 01:02:41.920
[Amit Varma]: do when they'll take a particular strand of history and they'll say

01:02:41.920 --> 01:02:44.920
[Amit Varma]: this is all there is and everything is because of this and this is what it

01:02:44.920 --> 01:02:47.920
[Amit Varma]: inevitably leads to and of course

01:02:47.920 --> 01:02:50.920
[Amit Varma]: right now I just went on a sort of rant against the wokes

01:02:50.920 --> 01:02:53.920
[Amit Varma]: but it's the same with the bhakts you know the wokes and the bhakts are

01:02:53.920 --> 01:02:56.920
[Amit Varma]: literally identical except that

01:02:56.920 --> 01:02:59.920
[Amit Varma]: you know they other a different kind of person and they adopt

01:02:59.920 --> 01:03:02.920
[Amit Varma]: different kinds of identities but otherwise

01:03:02.920 --> 01:03:05.920
[Amit Varma]: you know you are put in a category if you are a Muslim you are

01:03:05.920 --> 01:03:08.920
[Amit Varma]: a Muslim by definition this you know India doesn't matter

01:03:08.920 --> 01:03:11.920
[Amit Varma]: other identities don't matter and you are also

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:14.920
[Amit Varma]: supposed to be you know responsible for what happened in the

01:03:14.920 --> 01:03:17.920
[Guest]: past where not past you're supposed to be

01:03:17.920 --> 01:03:20.920
[Guest]: responsible for what happens in Afghanistan today right now

01:03:20.920 --> 01:03:23.920
[Guest]: so you might have never been out of India

01:03:23.920 --> 01:03:26.920
[Guest]: you might not have ever been out of your say city

01:03:26.920 --> 01:03:29.920
[Guest]: you can't place Afghanistan on the map

01:03:29.920 --> 01:03:32.920
[Guest]: you have to take responsibility for that

01:03:32.920 --> 01:03:35.920
[Guest]: that's the dominant narrative and the same way

01:03:35.920 --> 01:03:38.920
[Guest]: you have to you as a cishet

01:03:38.920 --> 01:03:41.920
[Guest]: you have to take responsibility for

01:03:41.920 --> 01:03:44.920
[Guest]: something for you know maybe your forefathers didn't even do that

01:03:44.920 --> 01:03:47.920
[Guest]: I mean it's not necessary that everyone's

01:03:47.920 --> 01:03:50.920
[Guest]: forefathers were zamindars and nobility right

01:03:50.920 --> 01:03:53.920
[Guest]: so for you know you might have a very humble beginning but

01:03:53.920 --> 01:03:56.920
[Guest]: it doesn't matter you have a certain surname

01:03:56.920 --> 01:03:59.920
[Guest]: and that's all that matters same way like Muslims have a certain name

01:03:59.920 --> 01:04:02.920
[Guest]: that matters it's very reductive and

01:04:02.920 --> 01:04:05.920
[Amit Varma]: very destructive actually and also there is the assumption

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:08.920
[Amit Varma]: like why should people assume I am either cishet or savanna

01:04:08.920 --> 01:04:11.920
[Amit Varma]: you know you have no way of knowing that

01:04:11.920 --> 01:04:14.920
[Amit Varma]: one it shouldn't matter but two you have no way of knowing that

01:04:14.920 --> 01:04:17.920
[Amit Varma]: so this kind of reductionism is something that kind of

01:04:17.920 --> 01:04:20.920
[Amit Varma]: bothers me so let's kind of come back to your personal

01:04:20.920 --> 01:04:23.920
[Amit Varma]: history that after 2014 you

01:04:23.920 --> 01:04:26.920
[Amit Varma]: discover this new love of you know reading history

