[Guest]: because and forget about elections

01:40:07.920 --> 01:40:10.920
[Guest]: look at things happening as recently

01:40:10.920 --> 01:40:13.920
[Guest]: as last year the Delhi riots yes there

01:40:13.920 --> 01:40:16.920
[Guest]: is a Mishra Singh Goli Maro and Gadaro

01:40:16.920 --> 01:40:19.920
[Guest]: and all that but who is the one actually

01:40:19.920 --> 01:40:22.920
[Guest]: doing carrying out those instructions

01:40:22.920 --> 01:40:25.920
[Guest]: on the ground they are not Brahmins Brahmins

01:40:25.920 --> 01:40:28.920
[Guest]: would not go out burning homes and stuff yes

01:40:28.920 --> 01:40:31.920
[Guest]: there would be some there would be some but the

01:40:31.920 --> 01:40:34.920
[Guest]: an overwhelming bulk of the foot soldiers they happen to

01:40:34.920 --> 01:40:37.920
[Guest]: come from a very well known well understood

01:40:37.920 --> 01:40:40.920
[Guest]: well recognized community and that community is

01:40:40.920 --> 01:40:43.920
[Guest]: you know now you could argue

01:40:43.920 --> 01:40:46.920
[Guest]: that you know unemployment has a very big role to

01:40:46.920 --> 01:40:49.920
[Guest]: play in this and but then I believe it goes far

01:40:49.920 --> 01:40:52.920
[Guest]: beyond unemployment I think it's

01:40:52.920 --> 01:40:55.920
[Guest]: it's more of a question of validation they do find

01:40:55.920 --> 01:40:58.920
[Guest]: validation under a common Hindu umbrella they feel empowered

01:40:58.920 --> 01:41:01.920
[Guest]: okay fine I have something I mean there is someone

01:41:01.920 --> 01:41:04.920
[Guest]: who is okay we have been oppressed for a very long time

01:41:04.920 --> 01:41:07.920
[Guest]: we have been under the Brahmins and at the bottom of the totem

01:41:07.920 --> 01:41:10.920
[Guest]: pole now there is something else that's even below me

01:41:10.920 --> 01:41:13.920
[Guest]: as a Hindu I can claim dominance over that something

01:41:13.920 --> 01:41:16.920
[Guest]: and that something is Muslim that's what they have been

01:41:16.920 --> 01:41:19.920
[Guest]: shown and it kind of appeals to their

01:41:19.920 --> 01:41:22.920
[Guest]: sense of you know supremacy

01:41:22.920 --> 01:41:25.920
[Guest]: which has never been entertained before

01:41:25.920 --> 01:41:28.920
[Guest]: so it works so yes you have

01:41:28.920 --> 01:41:31.920
[Guest]: to say it's a it's a master stroke but that's

01:41:31.920 --> 01:41:34.920
[Guest]: not something new in the Hindutva circles

01:41:34.920 --> 01:41:37.920
[Amit Varma]: I should also clarify that I think I can speak both on our behalf

01:41:37.920 --> 01:41:40.920
[Amit Varma]: when I say that when we say Hindutva hasn't been casteist we don't

01:41:40.920 --> 01:41:43.920
[Amit Varma]: mean that Hindu society is not casteist Hindu society

01:41:43.920 --> 01:41:46.920
[Amit Varma]: is deeply deeply casteist it's perhaps our biggest problem

01:41:46.920 --> 01:41:49.920
[Amit Varma]: but this is you know one thing that people often say is

01:41:49.920 --> 01:41:52.920
[Amit Varma]: that Hindutva and Hinduism is different and I agree with

01:41:52.920 --> 01:41:55.920
[Amit Varma]: that and Hindutva is far worse but in this particular

01:41:55.920 --> 01:41:58.920
[Amit Varma]: aspect this is one of those big flaws

01:41:58.920 --> 01:42:01.920
[Amit Varma]: in all of the traditions that encompass Hinduism

01:42:01.920 --> 01:42:04.920
[Amit Varma]: you know which is otherwise there are so many diverse

01:42:04.920 --> 01:42:07.920
[Amit Varma]: traditions within that and many of them are good things and many of them are not

01:42:07.920 --> 01:42:10.920
[Guest]: Hinduism is like a Russian doll you know those Madraska

01:42:10.920 --> 01:42:13.920
[Guest]: dolls like you can make as many divisions as you want

01:42:13.920 --> 01:42:16.920
[Guest]: and you'll never be done like first

01:42:16.920 --> 01:42:19.920
[Guest]: yeah there is lower caste upper caste OBC and what not then

01:42:19.920 --> 01:42:22.920
[Guest]: even within the upper caste there is Kshatriyas and Brahmins

01:42:22.920 --> 01:42:25.920
[Guest]: you think okay Brahmins are on top of the food chain no

01:42:25.920 --> 01:42:28.920
[Guest]: within Brahmins there is Brahmin A Brahmin B there is

01:42:28.920 --> 01:42:31.920
[Guest]: you know Mathil Brahmin and all kinds of

01:42:31.920 --> 01:42:34.920
[Guest]: Brahmins then they also discriminate within each other

01:42:34.920 --> 01:42:37.920
[Guest]: you know a Mishra for example would not would

01:42:37.920 --> 01:42:40.920
[Guest]: kind of look down upon a Tiwari and Tiwari would look down

01:42:40.920 --> 01:42:43.920
[Guest]: upon something else so there's a whole lot of

01:42:43.920 --> 01:42:46.920
[Guest]: subdivisions which we might not

01:42:46.920 --> 01:42:49.920
[Guest]: even be aware of and that subdivision

01:42:49.920 --> 01:42:52.920
[Guest]: you cannot just wish them away you can't

01:42:52.920 --> 01:42:55.920
[Guest]: what you can do is for example even in the West

01:42:55.920 --> 01:42:58.920
[Guest]: you can't wish away the Jews and

01:42:58.920 --> 01:43:01.920
[Guest]: the Christians and the you know

01:43:01.920 --> 01:43:04.920
[Guest]: and the Blacks and the Whites they are there

01:43:04.920 --> 01:43:07.920
[Guest]: what's needed in my books is

01:43:07.920 --> 01:43:10.920
[Guest]: the recognition that yes we are of different castes

01:43:10.920 --> 01:43:13.920
[Guest]: which in a way is what Gandhi tried to say but then again

01:43:13.920 --> 01:43:16.920
[Guest]: he was more on the side of virtue signaling

01:43:16.920 --> 01:43:19.920
[Guest]: so it's very hard to say how much of it he actually meant

01:43:19.920 --> 01:43:22.920
[Guest]: but you have to recognize that we are two different

01:43:22.920 --> 01:43:25.920
[Guest]: but we both have the same rights like a Dalit

01:43:25.920 --> 01:43:28.920
[Guest]: and a Brahmin can

01:43:28.920 --> 01:43:31.920
[Guest]: Dalit can continue being Dalit, a Brahmin can continue being Brahmin

01:43:31.920 --> 01:43:34.920
[Guest]: but at the same time instead of treating

01:43:34.920 --> 01:43:37.920
[Guest]: them as Dalit below Brahmin, Dalit and Brahmin

01:43:37.920 --> 01:43:40.920
[Amit Varma]: on the same on the same page well you know I would think

01:43:40.920 --> 01:43:43.920
[Amit Varma]: that for example I still don't know

01:43:43.920 --> 01:43:46.920
[Amit Varma]: what my caste is right and people will of course say correctly

01:43:46.920 --> 01:43:49.920
[Amit Varma]: that it is a sign of my privilege that I don't know my caste

01:43:49.920 --> 01:43:52.920
[Amit Varma]: and that's correct and I completely buy that but why is it a sign

01:43:52.920 --> 01:43:55.920
[Amit Varma]: of my privilege that I don't know my caste because I was fortunate enough to grow up

01:43:55.920 --> 01:43:58.920
[Amit Varma]: in a prosperous family which had done well for itself economically

01:43:58.920 --> 01:44:01.920
[Amit Varma]: and our incentives were aligned with treating

01:44:01.920 --> 01:44:04.920
[Amit Varma]: everybody with equal respect so the point is

01:44:04.920 --> 01:44:07.920
[Amit Varma]: if the economy grows if society prospers to that level

01:44:07.920 --> 01:44:10.920
[Amit Varma]: with none of which are a magic bullet but I would imagine

01:44:10.920 --> 01:44:13.920
[Amit Varma]: that things like urbanization and a growing economy

01:44:13.920 --> 01:44:16.920
[Amit Varma]: change your incentives to the point where you can't afford to

01:44:16.920 --> 01:44:19.920
[Amit Varma]: discriminate anymore you want to be part of larger economic networks

01:44:19.920 --> 01:44:22.920
[Amit Varma]: so which is why you know villages and rural India's caste

01:44:22.920 --> 01:44:25.920
[Amit Varma]: is far more pervasive there than in cities which is not to say they don't

01:44:25.920 --> 01:44:28.920
[Amit Varma]: exist in cities caste is everywhere in India

01:44:28.920 --> 01:44:31.920
[Amit Varma]: but it's it's kind of a little less so ideally what I

01:44:31.920 --> 01:44:34.920
[Amit Varma]: would like is you are born what you are born but that caste consciousness

01:44:34.920 --> 01:44:37.920
[Amit Varma]: is not there when you meet someone yeah if

01:44:37.920 --> 01:44:40.920
[Amit Varma]: if I meet you at a party and somebody says hey Amit meet Amit

01:44:40.920 --> 01:44:43.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm not going to ask you your surname to try and figure out what your caste must be

01:44:43.920 --> 01:44:46.920
[Amit Varma]: exactly that's what we want to remove because

01:44:46.920 --> 01:44:49.920
[Guest]: you know that's the thing you can't

01:44:49.920 --> 01:44:52.920
[Guest]: like no matter how much you wish for a utopia

01:44:52.920 --> 01:44:55.920
[Amit Varma]: it's just not happening no I it isn't happening now

01:44:55.920 --> 01:44:58.920
[Amit Varma]: but I think with urbanization prosperity they become less and less

01:44:58.920 --> 01:45:01.920
[Guest]: your incentive change it will definitely become diluted

01:45:01.920 --> 01:45:04.920
[Guest]: diluted to the extent I mean frankly

01:45:04.920 --> 01:45:07.920
[Guest]: speaking before this whole Hindutva

01:45:07.920 --> 01:45:10.920
[Guest]: and you know the virtue signaling the wokeism

01:45:10.920 --> 01:45:13.920
[Guest]: and the saffronism everything going extreme in different

01:45:13.920 --> 01:45:16.920
[Guest]: directions before this phase I had actually

01:45:16.920 --> 01:45:19.920
[Guest]: come to believe that caste doesn't exist in Bombay at least

01:45:19.920 --> 01:45:22.920
[Guest]: anywhere else I don't know but at least in Mumbai it doesn't exist

01:45:22.920 --> 01:45:25.920
[Guest]: because over the years that I have been working we used to eat together

01:45:25.920 --> 01:45:28.920
[Guest]: I still can't tell somebody's caste from their surname

01:45:28.920 --> 01:45:31.920
[Unknown]: maybe if somebody says I'm a Mishra then I would know

01:45:31.920 --> 01:45:34.920
[Guest]: Mishra means you are a Brahmin but when you

01:45:34.920 --> 01:45:37.920
[Guest]: live in a city like Bombay it's so cosmopolitan

01:45:37.920 --> 01:45:40.920
[Guest]: on a daily basis you come across some 100 different surnames

01:45:40.920 --> 01:45:43.920
[Guest]: you wouldn't have known every single one of them

01:45:43.920 --> 01:45:46.920
[Guest]: you don't have a database of surnames so you can't map

01:45:46.920 --> 01:45:49.920
[Guest]: and it didn't bother me and it didn't bother people around me

01:45:49.920 --> 01:45:52.920
[Guest]: you can say ok fine I'm coming from a place of privilege

01:45:52.920 --> 01:45:55.920
[Guest]: but is everyone being privileged there like if I'm working

01:45:55.920 --> 01:45:58.920
[Guest]: somewhere I'm pretty sure there must be some people

01:45:58.920 --> 01:46:01.920
[Guest]: from the underprivileged class or caste

01:46:01.920 --> 01:46:04.920
[Guest]: or any such background but

01:46:04.920 --> 01:46:07.920
[Guest]: nobody seemed to bother I can't eat with you

01:46:07.920 --> 01:46:10.920
[Guest]: I can't share table with you because you are XYZ caste

01:46:10.920 --> 01:46:13.920
[Guest]: it's again exacerbating I think

01:46:13.920 --> 01:46:16.920
[Guest]: because of whatever political reasons

01:46:16.920 --> 01:46:19.920
[Amit Varma]: yeah so here's a question

01:46:19.920 --> 01:46:22.920
[Amit Varma]: and it begins with sort of a philosophical observation

01:46:22.920 --> 01:46:25.920
[Amit Varma]: and then goes on to a historical observation

01:46:25.920 --> 01:46:28.920
[Amit Varma]: and then goes on to your personal experience of studying history

01:46:28.920 --> 01:46:31.920
[Amit Varma]: and the philosophical observation is that increasingly

01:46:31.920 --> 01:46:34.920
[Amit Varma]: the more I think about it I begin to conclude

01:46:34.920 --> 01:46:37.920
[Amit Varma]: that there is no such thing as free will in the sense

01:46:37.920 --> 01:46:40.920
[Amit Varma]: the thinking behind this is that look if you know the state of every atom

01:46:40.920 --> 01:46:43.920
[Amit Varma]: in the universe at a given point in time

01:46:43.920 --> 01:46:46.920
[Amit Varma]: and their state in terms of where they are moving and what's happening

01:46:46.920 --> 01:46:49.920
[Amit Varma]: and all that you can predict the next moment and so on and so forth

01:46:49.920 --> 01:46:52.920
[Amit Varma]: down the line the reason we can't predict the next moment

01:46:52.920 --> 01:46:55.920
[Amit Varma]: is lack of knowledge which is why we need probabilistic

01:46:55.920 --> 01:46:58.920
[Amit Varma]: thinking to make sense of you know with the very limited

01:46:58.920 --> 01:47:01.920
[Amit Varma]: information we have what can we tell about what's going to

01:47:01.920 --> 01:47:04.920
[Amit Varma]: happen but if there was complete knowledge you would realize

01:47:04.920 --> 01:47:07.920
[Amit Varma]: that you know there is no such thing as free will though the illusion

01:47:07.920 --> 01:47:10.920
[Amit Varma]: of free will is necessary so that we can assign

01:47:10.920 --> 01:47:13.920
[Amit Varma]: responsibility now I don't know if you've thought about philosophy

01:47:13.920 --> 01:47:16.920
[Amit Varma]: so I won't ask you for your opinion on this but the

01:47:16.920 --> 01:47:19.920
[Amit Varma]: historical observation is this and let's go back to Savarkar because

01:47:19.920 --> 01:47:22.920
[Amit Varma]: it's very interesting that it seems to me that people are shaped

01:47:22.920 --> 01:47:25.920
[Amit Varma]: by their circumstances in greater ways

01:47:25.920 --> 01:47:28.920
[Amit Varma]: than we realize like in a sense Gandhi's career

01:47:28.920 --> 01:47:31.920
[Amit Varma]: as a social reformer started because as a lawyer

01:47:31.920 --> 01:47:34.920
[Amit Varma]: instead of getting the job in Bombay which he wanted he didn't

01:47:34.920 --> 01:47:37.920
[Amit Varma]: get that he got a gig in South Africa he went there and

01:47:37.920 --> 01:47:40.920
[Amit Varma]: you know there a certain set of people were his clients and he

01:47:40.920 --> 01:47:43.920
[Amit Varma]: entered all of those different kind of struggles and he got

01:47:43.920 --> 01:47:46.920
[Amit Varma]: kicked out of a train and generally a series

01:47:46.920 --> 01:47:49.920
[Amit Varma]: of accidents just took him in a particular direction which made him

01:47:49.920 --> 01:47:52.920
[Amit Varma]: what he was similarly with Savarkar you know

01:47:52.920 --> 01:47:55.920
[Amit Varma]: an observation that I remember making a long time back

01:47:55.920 --> 01:47:58.920
[Amit Varma]: about him and then later Manu Pillay also made it in something he wrote

01:47:58.920 --> 01:48:01.920
[Amit Varma]: is that if Savarkar died in 2010 we would think of him as we think

01:48:01.920 --> 01:48:04.920
[Amit Varma]: of Bhagat Singh today he was a violent revolutionary

01:48:04.920 --> 01:48:07.920
[Amit Varma]: I think in 1910 rather I think when he

01:48:07.920 --> 01:48:10.920
[Amit Varma]: in 1909 I think he met Gandhi in London

01:48:10.920 --> 01:48:13.920
[Amit Varma]: and they were both very impressed by each other and in a sense

01:48:13.920 --> 01:48:16.920
[Amit Varma]: in terms of values his values were identical

01:48:16.920 --> 01:48:19.920
[Amit Varma]: to Gandhi except in one sense at that time except

01:48:19.920 --> 01:48:22.920
[Amit Varma]: in one sense which is that Savarkar believed in violent methods

01:48:22.920 --> 01:48:25.920
[Amit Varma]: he was part of the infamous India house in London and

01:48:25.920 --> 01:48:28.920
[Amit Varma]: he used to hang around with Shyamji Krishna Verma and all of those guys

01:48:28.920 --> 01:48:31.920
[Amit Varma]: and you know a lot of shit used to go

01:48:31.920 --> 01:48:34.920
[Amit Varma]: down there and he was arrested for those violent activities

01:48:34.920 --> 01:48:37.920
[Amit Varma]: and at that time he's given speeches where he's talking about

01:48:37.920 --> 01:48:40.920
[Amit Varma]: he was always anti-caste but at that time pre 1910

01:48:40.920 --> 01:48:43.920
[Amit Varma]: all his speeches he's talking about Hindus and Muslims both have to

01:48:43.920 --> 01:48:46.920
[Amit Varma]: stand together we are the same people blah blah blah then what happens

01:48:46.920 --> 01:48:49.920
[Amit Varma]: in the Andaman's period is one he's tortured brutally

01:48:49.920 --> 01:48:52.920
[Amit Varma]: two it's not the British jailers who torture him directly

01:48:52.920 --> 01:48:55.920
[Amit Varma]: they have like a subclass of Muslim

01:48:55.920 --> 01:48:58.920
[Amit Varma]: sub-jailers who are Pathans and all of these people who carry out

01:48:58.920 --> 01:49:01.920
[Amit Varma]: the torture now I don't want to talk about the torture on this show

01:49:01.920 --> 01:49:04.920
[Amit Varma]: you can read either Vaibhav Purandhare's or Vikram Sampath's

01:49:04.920 --> 01:49:07.920
[Amit Varma]: book or just go to the not just Savarkar's

01:49:07.920 --> 01:49:10.920
[Amit Varma]: Andaman diaries but the Andaman's diaries of the people who were

01:49:10.920 --> 01:49:13.920
[Amit Varma]: imprisoned there with him it's horrifying it's brutal right

01:49:13.920 --> 01:49:16.920
[Amit Varma]: and over a decade long period of torture

01:49:16.920 --> 01:49:19.920
[Amit Varma]: because it's these Muslims torturing him

01:49:19.920 --> 01:49:22.920
[Amit Varma]: he comes to hate Muslims right so when he goes

01:49:22.920 --> 01:49:25.920
[Amit Varma]: into prison he's like India belongs to Hindus and Muslims

01:49:25.920 --> 01:49:28.920
[Amit Varma]: he comes out of prisons he's like Muslims are the other

01:49:28.920 --> 01:49:31.920
[Amit Varma]: India belongs to Hindus and this whole thing in his book Hindutva

01:49:31.920 --> 01:49:34.920
[Amit Varma]: the argument that he makes seems like a rationalization

01:49:34.920 --> 01:49:37.920
[Amit Varma]: for this hatred that he has come to have

01:49:37.920 --> 01:49:40.920
[Amit Varma]: where he says that India is only a country of those

01:49:40.920 --> 01:49:43.920
[Amit Varma]: religions which also have their holy land here

01:49:43.920 --> 01:49:46.920
[Amit Varma]: and so Hindus are ok, Buddhists are ok, Jains are ok

01:49:46.920 --> 01:49:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Sikhs are ok but Muslims are not and

01:49:49.920 --> 01:49:52.920
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me that this silly argument is just

01:49:52.920 --> 01:49:55.920
[Amit Varma]: sort of a rational for the way that he already feels

01:49:55.920 --> 01:49:58.920
[Amit Varma]: resentment and he feels that resentment

01:49:58.920 --> 01:50:01.920
[Amit Varma]: because of what has happened to him and everything is kind of

01:50:01.920 --> 01:50:04.920
[Amit Varma]: circumstances and you look at his whole life

01:50:04.920 --> 01:50:07.920
[Amit Varma]: you put in counterfactual somewhere you change some of the circumstances

01:50:07.920 --> 01:50:10.920
[Amit Varma]: you change some of that formula and everything is different

01:50:10.920 --> 01:50:13.920
[Amit Varma]: if he dies in 1910 he is a hero today to us

01:50:13.920 --> 01:50:16.920
[Amit Varma]: and everybody is trying to claim him like they are trying to claim Bhagat Singh

01:50:16.920 --> 01:50:19.920
[Amit Varma]: or if he isn't sent to the Andaman's let's say

01:50:19.920 --> 01:50:22.920
[Amit Varma]: he is sent somewhere else something else happens

01:50:22.920 --> 01:50:25.920
[Amit Varma]: you really never know so my question to you leading up from

01:50:25.920 --> 01:50:28.920
[Amit Varma]: this philosophical observation about free will and this

01:50:28.920 --> 01:50:31.920
[Amit Varma]: historical observation about Gandhi and Savarkar is

01:50:31.920 --> 01:50:34.920
[Amit Varma]: that as you read history do you also then get this sense

01:50:34.920 --> 01:50:37.920
[Amit Varma]: that these circumstances are everything that what we

01:50:37.920 --> 01:50:40.920
[Amit Varma]: are in a sense is contingent on the accidents that happen to us

01:50:40.920 --> 01:50:43.920
[Guest]: we absolutely are and everything has to be

01:50:43.920 --> 01:50:46.920
[Guest]: is has been contingent to

01:50:46.920 --> 01:50:49.920
[Guest]: what your incentives are for every step you take

01:50:49.920 --> 01:50:52.920
[Guest]: and what detriments you have to face

01:50:52.920 --> 01:50:55.920
[Guest]: a whole lot of them might not even be aware

01:50:55.920 --> 01:50:58.920
[Guest]: might not even be known to us we might never get to know

01:50:58.920 --> 01:51:01.920
[Guest]: everything we might never get to know

01:51:01.920 --> 01:51:04.920
[Guest]: all that Savarkar had to go through

01:51:04.920 --> 01:51:07.920
[Guest]: to either justify or colour his actions

01:51:07.920 --> 01:51:10.920
[Guest]: in much worse light either way

01:51:10.920 --> 01:51:13.920
[Guest]: we don't know now there is one very

01:51:13.920 --> 01:51:16.920
[Guest]: favourite saying from Greece

01:51:16.920 --> 01:51:19.920
[Guest]: that I love that for situations like this

01:51:19.920 --> 01:51:22.920
[Guest]: it's called Athena's owl flies only at dusk

01:51:22.920 --> 01:51:25.920
[Guest]: so Athena is this Greek goddess

01:51:25.920 --> 01:51:28.920
[Guest]: of wisdom like Saraswati of the Greeks

01:51:28.920 --> 01:51:31.920
[Guest]: and actually it's Minerva but Athena is the

01:51:31.920 --> 01:51:34.920
[Guest]: Roman equivalent so

01:51:34.920 --> 01:51:37.920
[Guest]: she has an owl I mean surprisingly

01:51:37.920 --> 01:51:40.920
[Guest]: because Saraswati also has an owl and that owl is

01:51:40.920 --> 01:51:43.920
[Guest]: said to fly only at dusk because typically owls fly at dusk

01:51:43.920 --> 01:51:46.920
[Guest]: all day because they can't see in daylight

01:51:46.920 --> 01:51:49.920
[Guest]: so what this actually means is that

01:51:49.920 --> 01:51:52.920
[Guest]: wisdom only comes in hindsight

01:51:52.920 --> 01:51:55.920
[Guest]: so today Athena's owl is

01:51:55.920 --> 01:51:58.920
[Guest]: a metaphor for wisdom so wisdom only flies

01:51:58.920 --> 01:52:01.920
[Guest]: at dusk so all day what happened

01:52:01.920 --> 01:52:04.920
[Guest]: at night you can sit and reflect

01:52:04.920 --> 01:52:07.920
[Guest]: and you can argue with yourself

01:52:07.920 --> 01:52:10.920
[Guest]: I could have done that I should have done this

01:52:10.920 --> 01:52:13.920
[Guest]: when I had a fight with somebody in the morning and then

01:52:13.920 --> 01:52:16.920
[Guest]: in the evening I might sit and think why didn't I say this

01:52:16.920 --> 01:52:19.920
[Guest]: I could have told him this this would have been such a wonderful retort

01:52:19.920 --> 01:52:22.920
[Guest]: but then in the heat of the moment I might not come up with

01:52:22.920 --> 01:52:25.920
[Guest]: such ideas I might not have the time or incentive or even the

01:52:25.920 --> 01:52:28.920
[Guest]: wisdom to think those things so I believe it's

01:52:28.920 --> 01:52:31.920
[Guest]: the same with historical characters

01:52:31.920 --> 01:52:34.920
[Guest]: a. they are contingent on what's happening around them

01:52:34.920 --> 01:52:37.920
[Guest]: and b. it's also contingent on their idea of

01:52:37.920 --> 01:52:40.920
[Guest]: good and bad because like we discussed

01:52:40.920 --> 01:52:43.920
[Guest]: about human zoos what's good

01:52:43.920 --> 01:52:46.920
[Guest]: and what's moral rather and what's immoral

01:52:46.920 --> 01:52:49.920
[Guest]: it's a very fuzzy definition and the definition changes every

01:52:49.920 --> 01:52:52.920
[Guest]: decade I won't even say century every decade what

01:52:52.920 --> 01:52:55.920
[Guest]: was considered moral 10 years ago might be immoral

01:52:55.920 --> 01:52:58.920
[Guest]: today there are so many new words

01:52:58.920 --> 01:53:01.920
[Guest]: that we grew up saying today we can't say those things because

01:53:01.920 --> 01:53:04.920
[Guest]: at least not in polite circles right within

01:53:04.920 --> 01:53:07.920
[Guest]: my lifetime ass has come to mean a body part

01:53:07.920 --> 01:53:10.920
[Guest]: while earlier it used to be an animal

01:53:10.920 --> 01:53:13.920
[Guest]: and the same thing with so many other words so

01:53:13.920 --> 01:53:16.920
[Guest]: I remember when I was a kid we could say

01:53:16.920 --> 01:53:19.920
[Guest]: I have read in academic books the word negro

01:53:19.920 --> 01:53:22.920
[Guest]: today you say that word and no you can't

01:53:22.920 --> 01:53:25.920
[Guest]: you just can't you will be ostracized so things evolve

01:53:25.920 --> 01:53:28.920
[Guest]: now one example is George

01:53:28.920 --> 01:53:31.920
[Guest]: Washington we know him as the great freedom fighter

01:53:31.920 --> 01:53:34.920
[Guest]: one of the founding fathers of America and

01:53:34.920 --> 01:53:37.920
[Guest]: a great patriot above all now what he did to

01:53:37.920 --> 01:53:40.920
[Guest]: other races it's not

01:53:40.920 --> 01:53:43.920
[Guest]: very much in public domain he had slaves

01:53:43.920 --> 01:53:46.920
[Guest]: and slaves of course didn't have blacks didn't have

01:53:46.920 --> 01:53:49.920
[Guest]: much of a voting right back then or any other rights

01:53:49.920 --> 01:53:52.920
[Guest]: but George Washington himself having slaves

01:53:52.920 --> 01:53:55.920
[Guest]: of his own he inherited some he bought

01:53:55.920 --> 01:53:58.920
[Guest]: some and did some horrible things to them including

01:53:58.920 --> 01:54:01.920
[Guest]: that one time where he he lost

01:54:01.920 --> 01:54:04.920
[Guest]: a bunch of his teeth and he had

01:54:04.920 --> 01:54:07.920
[Guest]: tooth taken out of one of his slaves

01:54:07.920 --> 01:54:10.920
[Guest]: to be transplanted into his own gums so

01:54:10.920 --> 01:54:13.920
[Guest]: those kind of things and of course

01:54:13.920 --> 01:54:16.920
[Guest]: you being a slave you can't say no there is

01:54:16.920 --> 01:54:19.920
[Guest]: just no scope so somebody like George Washington

01:54:19.920 --> 01:54:22.920
[Guest]: he thought that was ok because they are slaves

