02:20:52.920 --> 02:20:55.920
[Amit Varma]: okay okay one sec

02:20:55.920 --> 02:20:58.920
[Amit Varma]: here's another interesting thought that I have been having

02:20:58.920 --> 02:21:01.920
[Amit Varma]: over the last few years and let me see what you think of it

02:21:01.920 --> 02:21:04.920
[Amit Varma]: and which is that in the times that we grew up in

02:21:04.920 --> 02:21:07.920
[Amit Varma]: and we are both in our 40s grew up in the 80s and 90s and so on

02:21:07.920 --> 02:21:11.920
[Amit Varma]: we had a notion of what art is like

02:21:11.920 --> 02:21:14.920
[Amit Varma]: what storytelling is like what literature is like in terms of form

02:21:14.920 --> 02:21:17.920
[Amit Varma]: right so if you want to be a writer you might want to write a book

02:21:17.920 --> 02:21:20.920
[Amit Varma]: or if you want to do journalism you might want to write articles

02:21:20.920 --> 02:21:23.920
[Amit Varma]: and they have certain kinds of conventional

02:21:23.920 --> 02:21:26.920
[Amit Varma]: lengths and certain conventional forms and all of that

02:21:26.920 --> 02:21:29.920
[Amit Varma]: now ditto if you want to make movies you either

02:21:29.920 --> 02:21:32.920
[Amit Varma]: make a full feature film which in the west could be 90 minutes

02:21:32.920 --> 02:21:35.920
[Amit Varma]: in India could be 3 hours or you make a short film and there are

02:21:35.920 --> 02:21:38.920
[Amit Varma]: lengths for that and so on and there's no flexibility

02:21:38.920 --> 02:21:41.920
[Amit Varma]: within these these are the forms

02:21:41.920 --> 02:21:44.920
[Amit Varma]: given to you for particular reasons and what I find

02:21:44.920 --> 02:21:47.920
[Amit Varma]: with creators in the modern age is because of technology

02:21:47.920 --> 02:21:50.920
[Amit Varma]: and the tools we have both the tools of production

02:21:50.920 --> 02:21:53.920
[Amit Varma]: the tools of dissemination the tools of consumption on the parts

02:21:53.920 --> 02:21:56.920
[Amit Varma]: of those who consume these that these

02:21:56.920 --> 02:21:59.920
[Amit Varma]: forms don't matter anymore that you know when I started

02:21:59.920 --> 02:22:02.920
[Amit Varma]: blogging I realized that like one reason it was so liberating

02:22:02.920 --> 02:22:05.920
[Amit Varma]: and like of course I was freed from gatekeepers freed from the

02:22:05.920 --> 02:22:08.920
[Amit Varma]: news cycle but the main reason it was liberating is I was

02:22:08.920 --> 02:22:11.920
[Amit Varma]: freed from constraints of form that a typical newspaper article

02:22:11.920 --> 02:22:14.920
[Amit Varma]: could be 800 words here I could do 80 or 80,000

02:22:14.920 --> 02:22:17.920
[Amit Varma]: I find a similar thing happening say with podcasts like I could

02:22:17.920 --> 02:22:20.920
[Amit Varma]: not do a 5 hour interview on radio right but when

02:22:20.920 --> 02:22:23.920
[Amit Varma]: I managed to do a 5 hour conversation on a show

02:22:23.920 --> 02:22:26.920
[Amit Varma]: like this because of the form it serves up a different

02:22:26.920 --> 02:22:29.920
[Amit Varma]: kind of content and tangentially it also changes me

02:22:29.920 --> 02:22:32.920
[Amit Varma]: into a different kind of person because I have to listen that much more

02:22:32.920 --> 02:22:35.920
[Amit Varma]: I have to kind of delve that much deeper and I am

02:22:35.920 --> 02:22:38.920
[Amit Varma]: essentially therefore a different person than I would have been

02:22:38.920 --> 02:22:41.920
[Amit Varma]: if instead of doing a 4 hour conversation every week for 5 years

02:22:41.920 --> 02:22:44.920
[Guest]: I did a half an hour conversation. You have to probably listen to the same

02:22:44.920 --> 02:22:47.920
[Guest]: conversation multiple times while you are editing

02:22:47.920 --> 02:22:50.920
[Amit Varma]: yeah so my question is that one form

02:22:50.920 --> 02:22:53.920
[Amit Varma]: that I see that you mastered and here also you have said

02:22:53.920 --> 02:22:56.920
[Amit Varma]: that it's taken you some time you don't like the stuff you did so much

02:22:56.920 --> 02:22:59.920
[Amit Varma]: in 2019 but one form that you say that you worked

02:22:59.920 --> 02:23:02.920
[Amit Varma]: on and I say that you mastered is the Twitter

02:23:02.920 --> 02:23:05.920
[Amit Varma]: storytelling format where over a Twitter thread

02:23:05.920 --> 02:23:08.920
[Amit Varma]: breaking it up into many many tweets you are telling this

02:23:08.920 --> 02:23:11.920
[Amit Varma]: incredibly engrossing story so much so

02:23:11.920 --> 02:23:14.920
[Amit Varma]: that if someone actually comes across you know one of

02:23:14.920 --> 02:23:17.920
[Amit Varma]: your tweet threads while you are in the process of composing it

02:23:17.920 --> 02:23:20.920
[Amit Varma]: there is no option but to sit there and keep refreshing and wait for

02:23:20.920 --> 02:23:23.920
[Amit Varma]: the story to complete itself right. At the same time you were

02:23:23.920 --> 02:23:26.920
[Amit Varma]: approached by Storytel and who are wonderful people

02:23:26.920 --> 02:23:29.920
[Amit Varma]: by the way great platform I have also done stuff for them I will link it from the show notes

02:23:29.920 --> 02:23:32.920
[Amit Varma]: but at the same time you were approached by them and there it's a

02:23:32.920 --> 02:23:35.920
[Amit Varma]: different kind of format it's an audio show someone's reading it

02:23:35.920 --> 02:23:38.920
[Amit Varma]: out you have to kind of write a script for that at some

02:23:38.920 --> 02:23:41.920
[Amit Varma]: point in the future I hope you will go on to write books as

02:23:41.920 --> 02:23:44.920
[Amit Varma]: well though again part of the reason if somebody approaches

02:23:44.920 --> 02:23:47.920
[Amit Varma]: you for a book number 1 they absolutely should I would love to read your books

02:23:47.920 --> 02:23:50.920
[Amit Varma]: but number 2 again a publisher who comes to you

02:23:50.920 --> 02:23:53.920
[Amit Varma]: to ask you to write a book would do so with a certain

02:23:53.920 --> 02:23:56.920
[Amit Varma]: structure and a certain form in mind while the truth is

02:23:56.920 --> 02:23:59.920
[Amit Varma]: that those don't matter anymore so what is your

02:23:59.920 --> 02:24:02.920
[Amit Varma]: thinking on structures and forms do you worry that

02:24:02.920 --> 02:24:05.920
[Amit Varma]: there is a particular form which a story fits

02:24:05.920 --> 02:24:08.920
[Amit Varma]: and that it might not have the same effect

02:24:08.920 --> 02:24:11.920
[Amit Varma]: if you try to force fit it into another form

02:24:11.920 --> 02:24:14.920
[Amit Varma]: or do you think that a great story can be

02:24:14.920 --> 02:24:17.920
[Amit Varma]: adapted into absolutely any format including

02:24:17.920 --> 02:24:20.920
[Amit Varma]: web series inshallah someone listening to this will approach you and ask you

02:24:20.920 --> 02:24:23.920
[Amit Varma]: to be a showrunner for any of these

02:24:23.920 --> 02:24:26.920
[Amit Varma]: incredible stories you have come up with but what are your thoughts on this

02:24:26.920 --> 02:24:29.920
[Guest]: I believe that you have to

02:24:29.920 --> 02:24:32.920
[Guest]: play a balancing act you cannot go all out and say

02:24:32.920 --> 02:24:35.920
[Guest]: this is how I do things and it has to

02:24:35.920 --> 02:24:38.920
[Guest]: work take it or leave it

02:24:38.920 --> 02:24:41.920
[Guest]: it doesn't work that way because I am not the only one doing this

02:24:41.920 --> 02:24:44.920
[Guest]: there are hundreds upon thousands of people

02:24:44.920 --> 02:24:47.920
[Guest]: now the only thing I

02:24:47.920 --> 02:24:50.920
[Guest]: might set myself apart in actually ironically

02:24:50.920 --> 02:24:53.920
[Guest]: speaking the only way I can set myself apart is in

02:24:53.920 --> 02:24:56.920
[Guest]: showing a certain level of flexibility

02:24:56.920 --> 02:24:59.920
[Guest]: and flexibility is something that

02:24:59.920 --> 02:25:02.920
[Guest]: I have learnt a lot of

02:25:02.920 --> 02:25:05.920
[Guest]: on twitter because twitter is a very strange platform

02:25:05.920 --> 02:25:08.920
[Guest]: it gives you a word count constraint

02:25:08.920 --> 02:25:11.920
[Guest]: not word count sorry character count constraint

02:25:11.920 --> 02:25:14.920
[Guest]: which is even more even stricter

02:25:14.920 --> 02:25:17.920
[Guest]: so with such a constraint it also gives you

02:25:17.920 --> 02:25:20.920
[Guest]: a lot of independence like you can put out a thread

02:25:20.920 --> 02:25:23.920
[Guest]: and that thread can be initially my first thread

02:25:23.920 --> 02:25:26.920
[Guest]: if I remember well

02:25:26.920 --> 02:25:29.920
[Guest]: not the satguru one the first history related thread

02:25:29.920 --> 02:25:32.920
[Guest]: was Indus valley thing and I believe it was

02:25:32.920 --> 02:25:35.920
[Guest]: 20 or 30 tweets long not very sure but somewhere in between

02:25:35.920 --> 02:25:38.920
[Guest]: less than 30 so

02:25:38.920 --> 02:25:41.920
[Guest]: I put that out with a lot of

02:25:41.920 --> 02:25:44.920
[Guest]: doubt 30 tweets like twitter

02:25:44.920 --> 02:25:47.920
[Guest]: is a platform meant for quick consumption people just

02:25:47.920 --> 02:25:50.920
[Guest]: want to read a tweet and move on who is going to read 30 tweets

02:25:50.920 --> 02:25:53.920
[Guest]: then it did catch fire and I mean

02:25:53.920 --> 02:25:56.920
[Guest]: catch fire in the sense from considering

02:25:56.920 --> 02:25:59.920
[Guest]: I had what less than 500

02:25:59.920 --> 02:26:02.920
[Guest]: followers at the time and then there are people

02:26:02.920 --> 02:26:05.920
[Guest]: there are hundreds upon thousands of people who are reading

02:26:05.920 --> 02:26:08.920
[Guest]: a 20 part thread of yours

02:26:08.920 --> 02:26:11.920
[Guest]: so I would say it caught fire for me but then

02:26:11.920 --> 02:26:14.920
[Guest]: later on I realized so I kept

02:26:14.920 --> 02:26:17.920
[Guest]: upping the ante so to say

02:26:17.920 --> 02:26:20.920
[Guest]: next tweet was 50 tweets long

02:26:20.920 --> 02:26:23.920
[Guest]: then I did a tweet on Punjab

02:26:23.920 --> 02:26:26.920
[Guest]: the 1984 events

02:26:26.920 --> 02:26:29.920
[Guest]: and funnily I did not

02:26:29.920 --> 02:26:32.920
[Guest]: plan it but it came out to be 84 tweets long

02:26:32.920 --> 02:26:35.920
[Amit Varma]: so that was not the plan

02:26:35.920 --> 02:26:38.920
[Guest]: but then I realized no matter how long

02:26:38.920 --> 02:26:41.920
[Guest]: my thread goes people read it

02:26:41.920 --> 02:26:44.920
[Guest]: people read and people ask for more so it happened

02:26:44.920 --> 02:26:47.920
[Guest]: so I really you know tested it

02:26:47.920 --> 02:26:50.920
[Guest]: to its limits with the

02:26:50.920 --> 02:26:53.920
[Guest]: one on Kashmir I had to put it on two parts part 1 and part 2

02:26:53.920 --> 02:26:56.920
[Guest]: and both were 160 tweets long

02:26:56.920 --> 02:26:59.920
[Guest]: so a total of 320 tweets so that was like me

02:26:59.920 --> 02:27:02.920
[Guest]: testing the absolute extent of

02:27:02.920 --> 02:27:05.920
[Guest]: how far you could push and even that worked

02:27:05.920 --> 02:27:08.920
[Guest]: so Twitter in a way gives you a constraint

02:27:08.920 --> 02:27:11.920
[Guest]: but also sets you free because your tweet

02:27:11.920 --> 02:27:14.920
[Guest]: has to be a certain number of characters

02:27:14.920 --> 02:27:17.920
[Guest]: but there can be as many tweets

02:27:17.920 --> 02:27:20.920
[Guest]: but at the same time what this format taught me

02:27:20.920 --> 02:27:23.920
[Guest]: is making sure every sentence

02:27:23.920 --> 02:27:26.920
[Guest]: you write counts because I cannot make

02:27:26.920 --> 02:27:29.920
[Guest]: even a single tweet boring like you have a hundred tweets

02:27:29.920 --> 02:27:32.920
[Guest]: in a story so every tweet has to be

02:27:32.920 --> 02:27:35.920
[Guest]: either a cliffhanger or something close to it

02:27:35.920 --> 02:27:38.920
[Guest]: every tweet has to have that wow effect

02:27:38.920 --> 02:27:41.920
[Guest]: so that people are tempted to go over to the next

02:27:41.920 --> 02:27:44.920
[Guest]: tweet so I have

02:27:44.920 --> 02:27:47.920
[Guest]: learned to treat every single tweet as a story in itself

02:27:47.920 --> 02:27:50.920
[Guest]: because that's the only chance and then the next tweet has to

02:27:50.920 --> 02:27:53.920
[Guest]: again be a story in itself it has to have all those

02:27:53.920 --> 02:27:56.920
[Guest]: ingredients all those so to speak masalas

02:27:56.920 --> 02:27:59.920
[Guest]: of a story within those 140

02:27:59.920 --> 02:28:02.920
[Guest]: or 280 characters and so on and so forth

02:28:02.920 --> 02:28:05.920
[Guest]: so this has given me a lot of discipline

02:28:05.920 --> 02:28:08.920
[Guest]: and that's the reason why when I moved over to

02:28:08.920 --> 02:28:11.920
[Guest]: the full feature writing format

02:28:11.920 --> 02:28:14.920
[Guest]: for story tell it did not really

02:28:14.920 --> 02:28:17.920
[Guest]: bog me down much because I already knew how to write

02:28:17.920 --> 02:28:20.920
[Guest]: an interesting story where although I wouldn't

02:28:20.920 --> 02:28:23.920
[Guest]: say I have mastered the craft because

02:28:23.920 --> 02:28:26.920
[Guest]: down the line I am pretty sure I am going to look back and say oh what the hell did I write

02:28:26.920 --> 02:28:29.920
[Guest]: this is so hilarious so cringy so it happens

02:28:29.920 --> 02:28:32.920
[Guest]: but to the best of my extent I have managed to

02:28:32.920 --> 02:28:35.920
[Guest]: learn one very very crucial lesson that

02:28:35.920 --> 02:28:38.920
[Guest]: if I write for story tell or if I

02:28:38.920 --> 02:28:41.920
[Guest]: wrote for a book for that matter then every paragraph

02:28:41.920 --> 02:28:44.920
[Guest]: I will not put fillers let's just

02:28:44.920 --> 02:28:47.920
[Guest]: put it that way there won't be any fillers there won't be

02:28:47.920 --> 02:28:50.920
[Guest]: okay word count it won't

02:28:50.920 --> 02:28:53.920
[Guest]: you won't get that feel it will have something it will be dense

02:28:53.920 --> 02:28:56.920
[Guest]: so I wouldn't have

02:28:56.920 --> 02:28:59.920
[Guest]: been able to put out because I used to sometimes write

02:28:59.920 --> 02:29:02.920
[Guest]: articles for myself you know I used to write

02:29:02.920 --> 02:29:05.920
[Guest]: and even before 2014

02:29:05.920 --> 02:29:08.920
[Guest]: but

02:29:08.920 --> 02:29:11.920
[Guest]: those I can clearly tell there were

02:29:11.920 --> 02:29:14.920
[Guest]: certain paragraphs that I could just take out

02:29:14.920 --> 02:29:17.920
[Guest]: this isn't necessary it's redundant

02:29:17.920 --> 02:29:20.920
[Guest]: but today I cannot say the same for

02:29:20.920 --> 02:29:23.920
[Guest]: even maybe one random line or so

02:29:23.920 --> 02:29:26.920
[Guest]: but otherwise everything is like okay there is some information in this

02:29:26.920 --> 02:29:29.920
[Guest]: so this wouldn't be possible without Twitter

02:29:29.920 --> 02:29:32.920
[Amit Varma]: yeah there is a structural parallel to that which is

02:29:32.920 --> 02:29:35.920
[Amit Varma]: you know Chuck Palaniuk once wrote about how he structured his

02:29:35.920 --> 02:29:38.920
[Amit Varma]: books and his thing was that he just wanted people to keep

02:29:38.920 --> 02:29:41.920
[Amit Varma]: reading obsessively and turning the pages so he'd have really

02:29:41.920 --> 02:29:44.920
[Amit Varma]: short chapters a page, page and a half and you know

02:29:44.920 --> 02:29:47.920
[Amit Varma]: you read the page, page and a half but the cost of reading the next chapter

02:29:47.920 --> 02:29:50.920
[Amit Varma]: is so low that you just turn the page and like that you get to the end

02:29:50.920 --> 02:29:53.920
[Amit Varma]: of the book and obviously you want to be exciting throughout I did an

02:29:53.920 --> 02:29:56.920
[Amit Varma]: episode with my friend Sonia Falero on her book The Good Girls

02:29:56.920 --> 02:29:59.920
[Amit Varma]: in January I think tackling a serious subject

02:29:59.920 --> 02:30:02.920
[Amit Varma]: the two girls who were found hanging from a tree a few

02:30:02.920 --> 02:30:05.920
[Amit Varma]: years ago in Uttar Pradesh and she went to the village and

02:30:05.920 --> 02:30:08.920
[Amit Varma]: spent four years writing this book about what exactly happened there

02:30:08.920 --> 02:30:11.920
[Amit Varma]: and for a really serious subject she actually used the same

02:30:11.920 --> 02:30:14.920
[Amit Varma]: structure which was really interesting because you had short one

02:30:14.920 --> 02:30:17.920
[Amit Varma]: and a half page chapters so you're constantly you keep reading

02:30:17.920 --> 02:30:20.920
[Amit Varma]: but the pace, the rhythm isn't fast in that way

02:30:20.920 --> 02:30:23.920
[Amit Varma]: like you would expect from an action thriller

02:30:23.920 --> 02:30:26.920
[Amit Varma]: all of that is normal but the way the chapters are structured

02:30:26.920 --> 02:30:29.920
[Amit Varma]: you kind of just keep reading and keep moving on

02:30:29.920 --> 02:30:32.920
[Amit Varma]: and you know what you said about I don't want any tweet to be

02:30:32.920 --> 02:30:35.920
[Amit Varma]: a filler or any para to be a filler like this goes with an advice

02:30:35.920 --> 02:30:38.920
[Amit Varma]: I give my writing students that every sentence you write must

02:30:38.920 --> 02:30:41.920
[Amit Varma]: either go forward or it must go deeper you know if it is

02:30:41.920 --> 02:30:44.920
[Amit Varma]: not doing one of those two things you gotta cut it out

02:30:44.920 --> 02:30:47.920
[Amit Varma]: yeah it should serve a purpose so I get that that twitter

02:30:47.920 --> 02:30:50.920
[Amit Varma]: is beautiful in that sense that there is an incentive towards

02:30:50.920 --> 02:30:53.920
[Amit Varma]: brevity in terms of the character limit but there is

02:30:53.920 --> 02:30:56.920
[Amit Varma]: also that unlimited space where you can really

02:30:56.920 --> 02:30:59.920
[Amit Varma]: sprawl out as long as you can kind of keep people

02:30:59.920 --> 02:31:02.920
[Amit Varma]: reading but to me the one pitfall of this

02:31:02.920 --> 02:31:05.920
[Amit Varma]: seems to be that one you are forced to break up

02:31:05.920 --> 02:31:08.920
[Amit Varma]: whatever you are writing about into tweet sized

02:31:08.920 --> 02:31:11.920
[Amit Varma]: chunks and the danger there is that you start thinking

02:31:11.920 --> 02:31:14.920
[Amit Varma]: that way also about the different tweet sized chunks

02:31:14.920 --> 02:31:17.920
[Amit Varma]: that you can you know break it up into

02:31:17.920 --> 02:31:20.920
[Amit Varma]: and therefore there might be a danger that what

02:31:20.920 --> 02:31:23.920
[Amit Varma]: the great Javed Akhtar Saab calls Theraav

02:31:23.920 --> 02:31:26.920
[Amit Varma]: you know those moments of quiet introspection those moments

02:31:26.920 --> 02:31:29.920
[Amit Varma]: in a story where nothing much happens you are just setting something up

02:31:29.920 --> 02:31:32.920
[Amit Varma]: you know there isn't enough space for those

02:31:32.920 --> 02:31:35.920
[Amit Varma]: yeah so what are your thoughts on this?

02:31:35.920 --> 02:31:38.920
[Guest]: yeah there are places where you have to

02:31:38.920 --> 02:31:41.920
[Guest]: put that Theraav but I believe in non-fiction

02:31:41.920 --> 02:31:44.920
[Guest]: there is that becomes less of an I wouldn't say that

02:31:44.920 --> 02:31:47.920
[Guest]: is never an issue but in non-fiction

02:31:47.920 --> 02:31:50.920
