[Guest]: Indian you can name earlier you wouldn't know

02:58:12.920 --> 02:58:15.920
[Guest]: who went who left who stayed and

02:58:15.920 --> 02:58:18.920
[Guest]: so that became the first travel account by an Indian

02:58:18.920 --> 02:58:21.920
[Guest]: for an Indian of a year because he basically wanted to

02:58:21.920 --> 02:58:24.920
[Guest]: write what he experienced in UK for Indians

02:58:24.920 --> 02:58:27.920
[Guest]: so that back home Indians should know there is a land called Europe

02:58:27.920 --> 02:58:30.920
[Guest]: and you know like you feel like telling everyone I went to Goa and this is what

02:58:30.920 --> 02:58:33.920
[Amit Varma]: we did this is what happened and it's interesting to kind of remember

02:58:33.920 --> 02:58:36.920
[Amit Varma]: and put it in perspective that there were no maps in those days

02:58:36.920 --> 02:58:39.920
[Amit Varma]: you can't go online and look at the world map of a place

02:58:39.920 --> 02:58:42.920
[Amit Varma]: and have a sense of where everything is at least not commercially available not to the layman

02:58:42.920 --> 02:58:45.920
[Amit Varma]: yeah so for the layperson when you hear of Europe

02:58:45.920 --> 02:58:48.920
[Amit Varma]: it's just a word there is no picture in your head

02:58:48.920 --> 02:58:51.920
[Amit Varma]: you can't even picture a map that oh India is over here

02:58:51.920 --> 02:58:54.920
[Amit Varma]: and Europe is over there and there is nothing

02:58:54.920 --> 02:58:57.920
[Amit Varma]: it's so weird to think of the world in that way

02:58:57.920 --> 02:59:00.920
[Amit Varma]: right when your knowledge is so

