[Guest]: and I mean hats off to the explorers

02:59:03.920 --> 02:59:06.920
[Guest]: who would just take a wooden boat and

02:59:06.920 --> 02:59:09.920
[Guest]: step out into the sea having no idea

02:59:09.920 --> 02:59:12.920
[Guest]: where they might end up crashing next

02:59:12.920 --> 02:59:15.920
[Guest]: and Columbus is a villain today

02:59:15.920 --> 02:59:18.920
[Guest]: people give him all kinds of name and very soon

02:59:18.920 --> 02:59:22.920
[Guest]: I am pretty sure you won't have a Columbus day in the US anymore

02:59:22.920 --> 02:59:25.920
[Guest]: but for all the bad things he did or didn't do

02:59:25.920 --> 02:59:28.920
[Guest]: he was a very courageous explorer

02:59:28.920 --> 02:59:31.920
[Guest]: you can't take that away from him

02:59:31.920 --> 02:59:34.920
[Amit Varma]: people just stepped out

02:59:34.920 --> 02:59:37.920
[Guest]: he was an Elon Musk of his time

02:59:37.920 --> 02:59:40.920
[Guest]: Atlantic Ocean is the most violent ocean on the planet

02:59:40.920 --> 02:59:43.920
[Guest]: and to just take a boat and sail out

02:59:43.920 --> 02:59:46.920
[Guest]: on a hunch that India might be this way

02:59:46.920 --> 02:59:49.920
[Amit Varma]: and when you don't know what's on the other side

02:59:49.920 --> 02:59:52.920
[Amit Varma]: today we know so it seems trivial

02:59:52.920 --> 02:59:55.920
[Amit Varma]: exactly

02:59:55.920 --> 02:59:58.920
[Amit Varma]: one of my favorite phrases in politics

02:59:58.920 --> 03:00:01.920
[Amit Varma]: which is nattering nabobs of negativism

03:00:01.920 --> 03:00:04.920
[Amit Varma]: which was used by the vice president Spiro Agnew

03:00:04.920 --> 03:00:07.920
[Amit Varma]: to describe members of the media

03:00:07.920 --> 03:00:10.920
[Amit Varma]: so indeed it could be said anywhere by people in government

03:00:10.920 --> 03:00:13.920
[Amit Varma]: that the media is full of nattering nabobs of negativism

03:00:13.920 --> 03:00:16.920
[Amit Varma]: except in India where the media

03:00:16.920 --> 03:00:19.920
[Amit Varma]: is quite nice to the government these days

03:00:19.920 --> 03:00:22.920
[Amit Varma]: the pleasing pashas of positivism

03:00:22.920 --> 03:00:25.920
[Amit Varma]: that's what I would call the media of today

03:00:25.920 --> 03:00:28.920
[Amit Varma]: that's the first P word that came to mind

03:00:28.920 --> 03:00:31.920
[Amit Varma]: it is important indeed to alliterate

03:00:31.920 --> 03:00:34.920
[Guest]: so that's where the story of shampoo

03:00:34.920 --> 03:00:37.920
[Guest]: but this is not just a story of shampoo

03:00:37.920 --> 03:00:40.920
[Guest]: this is a story of the first time native Europeans

03:00:40.920 --> 03:00:43.920
[Guest]: tasting what is called Indian food

03:00:43.920 --> 03:00:46.920
[Amit Varma]: the first Indian restaurant

03:00:46.920 --> 03:00:49.920
[Guest]: any idea what was the menu like over there

03:00:49.920 --> 03:00:52.920
[Guest]: I think the menu wouldn't be very different

03:00:52.920 --> 03:00:55.920
[Guest]: from what it is today because by that time

03:00:55.920 --> 03:00:58.920
[Guest]: nearly everything that we eat today had been discovered

03:00:58.920 --> 03:01:01.920
[Guest]: and mainstreamed

03:01:01.920 --> 03:01:04.920
[Guest]: because all kinds of meat had been mainstreamed by then

03:01:04.920 --> 03:01:07.920
[Guest]: and potatoes and tomatoes which are all of foreign origin

03:01:07.920 --> 03:01:10.920
[Guest]: they had all been Indianized as early as

03:01:10.920 --> 03:01:13.920
[Guest]: 16th century

03:01:13.920 --> 03:01:16.920
[Guest]: so I doubt there would be any difference

03:01:16.920 --> 03:01:19.920
[Guest]: in the ingredients

03:01:19.920 --> 03:01:22.920
[Guest]: except for maybe how they cooked it

03:01:22.920 --> 03:01:25.920
[Guest]: that might be different but even that shouldn't be all that different

03:01:25.920 --> 03:01:28.920
[Guest]: that you wouldn't recognize them

03:01:28.920 --> 03:01:31.920
[Guest]: and it had to be simple because

03:01:31.920 --> 03:01:34.920
[Guest]: you have to also remember that

03:01:34.920 --> 03:01:37.920
[Guest]: carrying ingredients from India to Europe

03:01:37.920 --> 03:01:40.920
[Guest]: was not a very easy task back then

03:01:40.920 --> 03:01:43.920
[Guest]: you could not do that on a routine basis

03:01:43.920 --> 03:01:46.920
[Guest]: you have to use ingredients which are commonly available both sides of the ocean

03:01:46.920 --> 03:01:49.920
[Amit Varma]: so things like potatoes

03:01:49.920 --> 03:01:52.920
[Guest]: or rice or maybe wheat

03:01:52.920 --> 03:01:55.920
[Guest]: so it must be a very simple fare

03:01:55.920 --> 03:01:58.920
[Guest]: but with the Indian spices

03:01:58.920 --> 03:02:01.920
[Guest]: because Indian spices have been part of European markets

03:02:01.920 --> 03:02:04.920
[Amit Varma]: for at least a thousand years if not longer

03:02:04.920 --> 03:02:07.920
[Amit Varma]: so some proto chicken tikka masala no doubt

03:02:07.920 --> 03:02:10.920
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode with Vikram Doctor a long time ago on Indian food

03:02:10.920 --> 03:02:13.920
[Amit Varma]: and I will link that from the show notes but it is incredible

