[Amit Varma]: but yeah chickens for the win

03:03:46.920 --> 03:03:49.920
[Amit Varma]: before we end this episode let me ask you to tell another enjoyable story

03:03:49.920 --> 03:03:52.920
[Amit Varma]: which I know you love and I love as well

03:03:52.920 --> 03:03:55.920
[Amit Varma]: which is about the Indian connection to the American

03:03:55.920 --> 03:03:58.920
[Guest]: War of Independence

03:03:58.920 --> 03:04:01.920
[Guest]: Indian connection on at least two levels if not more

03:04:01.920 --> 03:04:04.920
[Guest]: because you know the biggest the most crucial

03:04:04.920 --> 03:04:07.920
[Guest]: connecting thread is the East India Company

03:04:07.920 --> 03:04:10.920
[Guest]: the East India Company got the charter sometime around

03:04:10.920 --> 03:04:13.920
[Guest]: the early 1600s if I'm not wrong

03:04:13.920 --> 03:04:16.920
[Guest]: 1605 or 1609 somewhere in between

03:04:16.920 --> 03:04:19.920
[Guest]: and about

03:04:19.920 --> 03:04:22.920
[Guest]: that's about the period where

03:04:22.920 --> 03:04:25.920
[Guest]: a couple of other companies also got chartered during

03:04:25.920 --> 03:04:28.920
[Guest]: the first one was the London Company

03:04:28.920 --> 03:04:31.920
[Guest]: then there was one the Plymouth Company

03:04:31.920 --> 03:04:34.920
[Guest]: so these two companies the idea was East India Company would go

03:04:34.920 --> 03:04:37.920
[Guest]: East and those two companies

03:04:37.920 --> 03:04:40.920
[Guest]: London Company and Plymouth Company would go West

03:04:40.920 --> 03:04:43.920
[Guest]: and by West means the New World

03:04:43.920 --> 03:04:46.920
[Guest]: so they wanted to just explore both the sides of the world

03:04:46.920 --> 03:04:49.920
[Guest]: for trade and of course they didn't find any trade

03:04:49.920 --> 03:04:52.920
[Guest]: opportunity in America because it was all you know

03:04:52.920 --> 03:04:55.920
[Guest]: native tribals and they would not buy anything from you

03:04:55.920 --> 03:04:58.920
[Guest]: but they did find places where you can

03:04:58.920 --> 03:05:01.920
[Guest]: build your settlements and start settling people

03:05:01.920 --> 03:05:04.920
[Guest]: like they settled Australia so they did that

03:05:04.920 --> 03:05:07.920
[Guest]: the first settlement that came out was

03:05:07.920 --> 03:05:10.920
[Guest]: Virginia I believe and they named it Virginia after the Virgin Queen

03:05:10.920 --> 03:05:13.920
[Guest]: so Virginia Georgetown I believe

03:05:13.920 --> 03:05:16.920
[Guest]: was a city

03:05:16.920 --> 03:05:19.920
[Guest]: a small settlement in Virginia

03:05:19.920 --> 03:05:22.920
[Guest]: so the stories start nearly

03:05:22.920 --> 03:05:25.920
[Guest]: simultaneously American story and Indian story

03:05:25.920 --> 03:05:28.920
[Guest]: and then they progress in their own different directions both are

03:05:28.920 --> 03:05:31.920
[Guest]: now the only difference is India already had a

03:05:31.920 --> 03:05:34.920
[Guest]: very thriving culture very prominent

03:05:34.920 --> 03:05:37.920
[Guest]: and India has too many people right so a big population

03:05:37.920 --> 03:05:40.920
[Guest]: no matter how many whites come you just

03:05:40.920 --> 03:05:43.920
[Guest]: cannot wipe out native population this big

03:05:43.920 --> 03:05:46.920
[Guest]: and not just big we were not exactly tribals

03:05:46.920 --> 03:05:49.920
[Guest]: before the British came we were kings and queens and

03:05:49.920 --> 03:05:52.920
[Guest]: full politics of our own we had the Mughals

03:05:52.920 --> 03:05:55.920
[Guest]: and everything so while in India

03:05:55.920 --> 03:05:58.920
[Guest]: the British had to come and for that matter not just the British

03:05:58.920 --> 03:06:01.920
[Guest]: whoever came they had to either assimilate or

03:06:01.920 --> 03:06:04.920
[Guest]: rule as a minority ruler but in places like

03:06:04.920 --> 03:06:07.920
[Guest]: Australia and the New World what happened was

03:06:07.920 --> 03:06:10.920
[Guest]: that the native population was so small in number and

03:06:10.920 --> 03:06:13.920
[Guest]: so weak and so uncivilized

03:06:13.920 --> 03:06:16.920
[Guest]: I wouldn't say uncivilized I would say not on the same level

03:06:16.920 --> 03:06:19.920
[Guest]: of civilization as Europe that they were

03:06:19.920 --> 03:06:22.920
[Guest]: overwhelmed very easily so that's how

03:06:22.920 --> 03:06:25.920
[Guest]: America became white and Australia became white but India could not

03:06:25.920 --> 03:06:28.920
[Guest]: become white right so now what

03:06:28.920 --> 03:06:31.920
[Guest]: happened is towards I think 1770s

03:06:31.920 --> 03:06:34.920
[Guest]: so America had this

03:06:34.920 --> 03:06:37.920
[Guest]: very fine arrangement where tea was discovered in

03:06:37.920 --> 03:06:40.920
[Guest]: China tea made its way to Europe as early as 1500s

03:06:40.920 --> 03:06:43.920
[Guest]: and that was another story within

03:06:43.920 --> 03:06:46.920
[Guest]: Indian connection because you know the British didn't

03:06:46.920 --> 03:06:49.920
[Guest]: know tea and there was a marriage

03:06:49.920 --> 03:06:52.920
[Guest]: Catherine of Braganza from Portugal she married Charles II

03:06:52.920 --> 03:06:55.920
[Guest]: and then she brought the tea

03:06:55.920 --> 03:06:58.920
[Guest]: drinking the idea of tea and a chest

03:06:58.920 --> 03:07:01.920
[Guest]: of tea I believe in dowry and

03:07:01.920 --> 03:07:04.920
[Guest]: that's how Bombay also came to Britain in dowry

03:07:04.920 --> 03:07:07.920
[Guest]: so that's when Britain tasted tea and tea

03:07:07.920 --> 03:07:10.920
[Guest]: became very popular and that this is a good drink

03:07:10.920 --> 03:07:13.920
[Guest]: and good beverage and the demand

03:07:13.920 --> 03:07:16.920
[Guest]: for tea shot up so bad that it overtook

03:07:16.920 --> 03:07:19.920
[Guest]: coffee in Britain and they had to

03:07:19.920 --> 03:07:22.920
[Guest]: and the only place they could buy tea from was China and the only

03:07:22.920 --> 03:07:25.920
[Guest]: way China would sell tea is if you pay them in silver

03:07:25.920 --> 03:07:28.920
[Guest]: but there was not enough silver there was a

03:07:28.920 --> 03:07:31.920
[Guest]: point where the British Empire

03:07:31.920 --> 03:07:34.920
[Guest]: ran out of silver so badly that they had to figure out

03:07:34.920 --> 03:07:37.920
[Guest]: alternative ways so they started they learned from

03:07:37.920 --> 03:07:40.920
[Guest]: Afghanistan that opium can be grown but Afghanistan

03:07:40.920 --> 03:07:43.920
[Guest]: was not under Britain at that time it was an independent

03:07:43.920 --> 03:07:46.920
[Guest]: you know under tribal rule there was an emir

03:07:46.920 --> 03:07:49.920
[Guest]: and all those things so they started

03:07:49.920 --> 03:07:52.920
[Guest]: growing opium in Bengal

03:07:52.920 --> 03:07:55.920
[Guest]: and smuggling that opium into China and

03:07:55.920 --> 03:07:58.920
[Guest]: this is how the first opium war happened

03:07:58.920 --> 03:08:01.920
[Guest]: now what happened sometime in the 1770

03:08:01.920 --> 03:08:04.920
[Guest]: monsoon screwed up

03:08:04.920 --> 03:08:07.920
[Guest]: and Bengal had the biggest famine ever in

03:08:07.920 --> 03:08:10.920
[Guest]: recorded history the great Bengal famine

03:08:10.920 --> 03:08:13.920
[Guest]: because of that famine there was I think

03:08:13.920 --> 03:08:16.920
[Guest]: upwards of a million deaths in Bengal alone

03:08:16.920 --> 03:08:19.920
[Guest]: and of course it's not just people dying

03:08:19.920 --> 03:08:22.920
[Guest]: it's also taking away your revenues as

03:08:22.920 --> 03:08:25.920
[Guest]: the East India Company you are highly dependent on

03:08:25.920 --> 03:08:28.920
[Guest]: Lagaan and that Lagaan is not coming anymore so

03:08:28.920 --> 03:08:31.920
[Guest]: East India Company has to do something and that's

03:08:31.920 --> 03:08:34.920
[Guest]: when Westminster passed a law that the

03:08:34.920 --> 03:08:37.920
[Guest]: East India Company to recover its losses it will have

03:08:37.920 --> 03:08:40.920
[Guest]: the monopoly of selling tea in America

03:08:40.920 --> 03:08:43.920
[Guest]: and Americans

03:08:43.920 --> 03:08:46.920
[Guest]: had been receiving 90% of their tea through independent

03:08:46.920 --> 03:08:49.920
[Guest]: suppliers who are basically

03:08:49.920 --> 03:08:52.920
[Guest]: smugglers but East India Company now got

03:08:52.920 --> 03:08:55.920
[Guest]: the monopoly and also they were given tax

03:08:55.920 --> 03:08:58.920
[Guest]: exemption so this is something Americans

03:08:58.920 --> 03:09:01.920
[Guest]: found very offensive and they were like

03:09:01.920 --> 03:09:04.920
[Guest]: okay fine we have to pay taxes but the East India Company

03:09:04.920 --> 03:09:07.920
[Guest]: doesn't have to pay taxes and we are living here we are consumers

03:09:07.920 --> 03:09:10.920
[Guest]: we have to pay a very high

03:09:10.920 --> 03:09:13.920
[Guest]: price for that tea the same tea that our people used

03:09:13.920 --> 03:09:16.920
[Guest]: to smuggle in and now they cannot do that because

03:09:16.920 --> 03:09:19.920
[Guest]: now suddenly they are called smugglers and they were giving us

03:09:19.920 --> 03:09:22.920
[Guest]: tea for a much lower price less than half the price

03:09:22.920 --> 03:09:25.920
[Guest]: so why are we suffering so much and

03:09:25.920 --> 03:09:28.920
[Guest]: at that time I will give you another thread to this

03:09:28.920 --> 03:09:31.920
[Guest]: the first world war happened in 1914

03:09:31.920 --> 03:09:34.920
[Guest]: and that was because somebody died in Austria

03:09:34.920 --> 03:09:37.920
[Guest]: now a bigger world war you can call it a world war

03:09:37.920 --> 03:09:40.920
[Guest]: but it actually happened only within Europe

03:09:40.920 --> 03:09:43.920
[Guest]: so to call it world war seems kind of unfair

03:09:43.920 --> 03:09:46.920
[Guest]: but then fine that's how the terminology is

03:09:46.920 --> 03:09:49.920
[Guest]: but in the truest sense of the word a world war happened

03:09:49.920 --> 03:09:52.920
[Guest]: as early as 1745 and that actually

03:09:52.920 --> 03:09:55.920
[Guest]: happened all over the world and that also happened because somebody died in

03:09:55.920 --> 03:09:58.920
[Guest]: Austria yeah there was this

03:09:58.920 --> 03:10:01.920
[Guest]: king who the ruler of the

03:10:01.920 --> 03:10:04.920
[Guest]: Holy Roman Empire although it was not Roman but

03:10:04.920 --> 03:10:07.920
[Guest]: he died and he had a daughter Maria Teresa

03:10:07.920 --> 03:10:10.920
[Guest]: and she was the only heir to the throne

03:10:10.920 --> 03:10:13.920
[Guest]: and there was a war of whether

03:10:13.920 --> 03:10:16.920
[Guest]: she should succeed to the throne or not because she is a girl

03:10:16.920 --> 03:10:19.920
[Guest]: girl should not become queen I mean should not become the monarch

03:10:19.920 --> 03:10:22.920
[Guest]: there was a side that supported her there was a side that

03:10:22.920 --> 03:10:25.920
